{"title_page": "Eli Apple", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|American football cornerback}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Eli Apple\n| image               = Eli Apple.jpg\n| image_size          = 185\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Apple with the New York Giants in 2016\n| current_team        = Free agent\n| number              = \n| position            = [[Cornerback]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1995|8|9}}\n| birth_place         = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n| death_date          =\n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 1\n| weight_lbs          = 203\n| high_school         = [[Eastern Regional High School|Eastern Regional]]<br/>{{nowrap|([[Voorhees Township, New Jersey]])}}\n| college             = [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]]\n| draftyear           = 2016\n| draftround          = 1\n| draftpick           = 10\n| pastteams           = \n* [[New York Giants]] ({{NFL Year|2016}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2018}})\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] ({{NFL Year|2018}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2019}})\n| status              = \n|highlights=\n* [[Fiesta Bowl|Fiesta Bowl Champion]] ([[2016 Fiesta Bowl (January)|2016]])\n* [[College Football Playoff National Championship|CFP National Champion]] ([[2015 College Football Playoff National Championship|2015]])\n* [[Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl Champion]] ([[2015 Sugar Bowl|2015]])\n* [[Big Ten Football Championship Game|Big Ten Champion]] ([[2014 Big Ten Football Championship Game|2014]])\n* Defensive MVP of the [[2016 Fiesta Bowl (January)|2016 Fiesta Bowl]]\n|statleague=NFL\n|statweek=\n|statseason=2019\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n|statvalue1=233\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n|statvalue4=3\n|statlabel3=[[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n|statvalue3=4\n|statlabel2=[[Pass deflections]]\n|statvalue2=33\n|statlabel5=[[Interceptions]]\n|statvalue5=3\n|nfl=2555277\n}}\n\n'''Eli Apple''' (born August 9, 1995), formerly known as '''Eli Woodard''',<ref>{{cite news|title=College football recruiting 2013: Ohio State picks up top 2013 recruit in Eli Woodard|newspaper=Sporting News|date=May 15, 2012|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/ncaa-football/story/2012-02-16/ohio-state-buckeyes-recruiting-eli-woodard-urban-meyer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Eastern football star Eli Woodard picks Ohio State over Rutgers|date=February 16, 2012|newspaper=[[NJ.com]]|url=http://www.nj.com/hssports/blog/football/index.ssf/2012/02/eastern_football_star_eli_woodard_picks_ohio_state_over_rutgers.html}}</ref> is an [[American football]] [[cornerback]] who is a free agent. He played [[college football]] at [[Ohio State]], and was selected by the [[New York Giants]] with the 10th overall pick in the first round of the [[2016 NFL Draft]].\n\n==High school career==\nApple attended [[Eastern Regional High School]] in Voorhees, New Jersey and was teammates with [[Tennessee Titans]] [[Nickelback (gridiron football)|nickelback]] [[Logan Ryan]].  Apple was rated the top prospect in New Jersey in Rival's 2013 class and was ranked the 28th best prospect nationally. He received about twenty scholarship offers from [[University of Alabama|Alabama]], [[University of California|California]], [[Virginia Tech]], [[Boston College]], [[University of Wisconsin|Wisconsin]], [[University of Tennessee|Tennessee]], [[Purdue University|Purdue]], [[University of Miami|Miami]], [[Georgia Tech University|Georgia Tech]], [[University of Maryland|Maryland]], [[University of Michigan|Michigan]], [[University of Mississippi|Ole Miss]], [[University of Nebraska|Nebraska]], [[University of North Carolina|North Carolina]], [[North Carolina State University|NC State]], and [[Clemson University|Clemson]] and ranked his top three schools as [[Rutgers University|Rutgers]], [[Ohio State University|Ohio State]], and [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://n.rivals.com/content/prospects/9722| title=Rivals.com: Eli Apple| accessdate=January 5, 2017| website=n.rivals.com}}</ref> On February 12, 2012, he announced his verbal commitment to Ohio State after Rutgers head coach [[Greg Schiano]] left for the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.nj.com/articles/7749176/eastern_football_star_eli_woodard_picks_ohio_state_over_rutgers.amp| title=Eastern football star, Eli Woodard, picks Ohio State over Rutgers| accessdate=January 5, 2017| website=nj.com}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nApple enrolled at Ohio State in January 2013 as a five-star prospect (ESPN 150) and rated as high as the No. 11 prospect nationally on the ESPN 150. He was also rated as the No. 1 overall prospect in New Jersey and No. 6 cornerback prospect nationally by 247sports.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eli Apple Profile |publisher=Ohio State University |accessdate=March 24, 2015 |url=http://www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/eli_apple_838099.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150325193022/http://www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/eli_apple_838099.html |archivedate=March 25, 2015 }}</ref> He redshirted as a true freshman and went on to play in 2014 as a redshirt freshman.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ohio State football CB Eli Apple's transformation could stop Michigan from repeat passing success|publisher=The Plain Dealer, Cleveland, Ohio|date=November 25, 2014|url=http://www.cleveland.com/osu/index.ssf/2014/11/ohio_state_indiana_eli_apple_b.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Eli Apple making strides for Ohio State football |newspaper=The Lantern|date=October 17, 2014|url=http://thelantern.com/2014/10/eli-apple-making-strides-for-ohio-state-football/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ohio State football: Now healthy, Apple makes big impact at Nickelback|newspaper=The Columbus Dispatch|date=November 19, 2014|url=http://buckeyextra.dispatch.com/content/stories/2014/11/19/ohio-state-football-apple-11-19.html}}</ref> He played in the [[2015 Sugar Bowl]] and the [[2015 College Football Playoff National Championship]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Eastern\u2019s Eli Apple now a national champion with Ohio State Buckeyes |newspaper=Voorhees Sun|date=January 15, 2015|url=http://www.voorheessun.com/2015/01/15/easterns-eli-apple-now-national-champion-ohio-state-buckeyes/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=South Jersey's Eli Apple has a hand in Ohio State's Big Ten Championship shutout|newspaper=[[NJ.com]]|date=December 7, 2014|url=http://www.nj.com/rutgersfootball/index.ssf/2014/12/south_jerseys_eli_apple_has_a_hand_in_ohio_states_big_ten_championship_shutout.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Eastern High's Apple is 'fantastic' in Ohio State's victory|newspaper=Philadelphia Inquirer|date=January 15, 2015|url=http://articles.philly.com/2015-01-15/sports/58071036_1_marcus-mariota-oregon-coach-mark-helfrich-urban-meyer}}</ref> In his second season with the Buckeyes, he was the Defensive MVP.\n\n==Professional career==\n{{external media \n| video1 =\n[http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000639950/Eli-Apple-2016-Combine-Workout Eli Apple\u2019s NFL Combine Workout]\n| video2 =\n[http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000639940/Eli-Apple-40-yard-dash Eli Apple runs the 40-yard dash]\n| video3 =\n[http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000639991/Eli-Apple-makes-one-handed-grab-during-Combine-drills Eli Apple makes one-handed grab at combine]\n}}\nOn January 4, 2016, Apple announced his decision to forgo his remaining eligibility and enter the [[2016 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |title=NFL: Eastern grad Eli Apple declares for draft |url=https://www.courierpostonline.com/story/sports/nfl/2016/01/04/nfl-eastern-grad-eli-apple-declares-draft/78279316/ |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |newspaper=Courier Post| date=January 4, 2016}}</ref> Apple attended the [[NFL Scouting Combine]] and completed the majority of combine drills before suffering cramps.<ref>{{cite web |title=Combine confirmations: 11 prospects deserving of draft status |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000640478/article/combine-confirmations-11-prospects-deserving-of-draft-status |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=NFL.com |author=Reuter, Chad |date=March 1, 2016}}</ref> He finished with the tenth fastest time in the [[40-yard dash]] among all participating players at the NFL Combine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/top-performers#year=2016&workout=FORTY_YARD_DASH&position=QB-RB-WR-TE-S-DL-LB-CB-OL-SPEC|title=NFL Events: Combine Top Performers|website=www.nfl.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2016, Apple attended Ohio State\u2019s pro day, but opted to stand on his combine numbers and only performed the short shuttle, three-cone drill, and positional drills. Apple had pre-draft visits with multiple teams, including the [[Buffalo Bills]], [[San Francisco 49ers]], and [[Tennessee Titans]].<ref>{{cite web |title=49ers pre-draft visits tracker 2016: Who is on the radar? |url=https://www.ninersnation.com/2016/3/6/11162320/49ers-draft-visits-tracker-2016-workouts-combine-senior-bowl-shrine-game |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=ninersnation.com |author=Fucillo, David |date=April 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2016 NFL Draft: Tennessee Titans Draft Connections Tracker |url=https://www.musiccitymiracles.com/2016/4/4/11355248/2016-nfl-draft-tennessee-titans-draft-connections-tracker |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=musiccitymiracles.com |author=Lambert, Terry |date=April 4, 2016}}</ref> At the conclusion of the pre-draft process, Apple was projected to be an early to mid first round pick by NFL draft experts and scouts. He was ranked the third best cornerback prospect in the draft by DraftScout.com, was ranked the fourth best cornerback by NFL analyst [[Mike Mayock]], and was ranked the sixth best defensive back by [[Sports Illustrated]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=126576&draftyear=2016&genpos=CB| title=*Eli Apple, DS #3 CB, Ohio State: 2016 NFL Draft| accessdate=January 5, 2017| website=nfldraftscout.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2016 NFL Draft Position Rankings |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2016/04/12/nfl-draft-2016-position-rankings-players-prospects |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=si.com |author=Burke, Chris |date=April 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mike Mayock's 2016 NFL Draft position rankings 5.0 |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000656285/article/mike-mayocks-2016-nfl-draft-position-rankings-50 |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=NFL.com |author=Mike Mayock |date=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n{{external media\n| video1 =\n[http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000657045/Giants-pick-Eli-Apple-No-10 Giants draft Eli Apple 10th overall]\n| video2 =\n[http://www.nfl.com/videos/new-york-giants/0ap3000000657164/Highlights-Giants-draft-CB-Eli-Apple NFL Draft Profile: Eli Apple]\n}}\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 0\u215d\n|       weight = 199\n|         dash = 4.40\n|    ten split = 1.53\n| twenty split = 2.59\n|      shuttle = 4.08\n|   cone drill = 7.00\n|     vertical = \n|     broad ft = \n|     broad in = \n|        bench = 13\n|    wonderlic = 21<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/eli-apple-ohio-state-anonymous-scout-042716|title=Eli Apple's mom responds after anonymous NFL scout disses her son|first=Aaron|last=Torres|date=April 27, 2016|accessdate=July 16, 2016|work=[[FoxSports.com]]}}</ref>\n|     arm span = 31\u215c\n|    hand span = 9\u215c\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]/Ohio State's Pro Day<ref name=\"draft\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/2016/profiles/eli-apple?id=2555277|title=NFL Events: Combine Player Profiles \u2013 Eli Apple|publisher=NFL.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===New York Giants===\nThe [[New York Giants]] selected Apple in the first round (10th overall) of the [[2016 NFL Draft]]. Apple was the second cornerback drafted in 2016, after [[Jalen Ramsey]] (5th overall).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.giants.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/New-York-Giants-Draft-Ohio-State-CB-Eli-Apple-in-first-round/2cd6e721-1696-42e9-8b29-ca363dc2c72d |title=New York Giants Draft Ohio State CB Eli Apple in first round |last=Salomone |first=Dan |date=April 29, 2016 |website=Giants.com |accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref> It was reported that the New York Giants has initially planned to draft linebacker [[Leonard Floyd]] or offensive tackle [[Jack Conklin]]. However, circumstances changed after [[Laremy Tunsil]] unexpectedly fell out of the top ten. The [[Tennessee Titans]] traded ahead of the Giants to draft Jack Conklin (8th overall) and the [[Chicago Bears]] traded ahead of the Giants to select Leonard Floyd (9th overall). New York Giants\u2019 General Manager [[Jerry Reese]] opted to keep the tenth overall pick and selected Apple who was their highest graded player available on their draft board without any issues or injuries.<ref>{{cite web |title=The bizarre circumstances that led to the Giants drafting Eli Apple |url=https://www.sny.tv/giants/news/the-bizarre-circumstances-that-led-to-the-giants-drafting-eli-apple/264057636 |accessdate=November 5, 2018 |website=sny.tv |date=December 27, 2017}}</ref> Draft analysts and fans criticized the selection of Apple as many deemed it to be a reach.<ref>{{cite web |title=Giants GM blasts draft critics bashing Eli Apple pick |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000659672/article/giants-gm-blasts-draft-critics-bashing-eli-apple-pick |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=NFL.com |author=Patra, Kevin |date=May 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Giants select Ohio State CB Eli Apple in first round |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/new-york-giants/post/_/id/46512/giants-select-ohio-state-cb-eli-apple-in-first-round |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |author=Graziano, Dan |date=April 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2016====\nOn May 6, 2016, the New York Giants signed Apple to a fully guaranteed four year, $15.15 million that includes a signing bonus of $9.21 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.giants.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/Giants-sign-four-draft-picks--14-undrafted-free-agents/bce88848-ed81-4d6a-8e99-26f19049be9d |title=Giants sign four draft picks & 14 undrafted free agents |last=Eisen |first=Michael |date=May 6, 2016 |website=Giants.com |accessdate=July 16, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803005711/http://www.giants.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/Giants-sign-four-draft-picks--14-undrafted-free-agents/bce88848-ed81-4d6a-8e99-26f19049be9d |archive-date=August 3, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|URL=http://overthecap.com/player/eli-apple/4723/|title=Over the cap.com:Eli Apple contract|accessdate=November 15, 2016|website=overthecap.com}}</ref>\n\nApple entered training camp slated as the third cornerback on the depth chart behind veterans [[Janoris Jenkins]] and [[Dominique Rodgers-Cromartie]].  Head coach [[Ben McAdoo]] named Apple the third cornerback on the depth chart to begin the regular season and first-team nickelback.\n\nHe made his professional regular season debut in the [[2016 New York Giants season|New York Giants\u2019]] season-opener at the [[2016 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] and recorded four solo tackles during their 20\u201319 victory. On September 25, 2016, Apple earned his first career start and recorded one solo tackle in a 29\u201327 loss to the [[2016 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]], but left the game in the second quarter after suffering hamstring injury. Apple was inactive for the Giants\u2019 Week 4 loss at the [[2016 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]] with a hamstring injury. He was also sidelined for their Week 6 win against the [[2016 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] due to a groin injury.<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.nj.com/articles/19386255/giants_may_without_eli_apple_and_dominique_rodgers.amp| title=Giants may be with Eli Apple and Dominique Rodgers-Cromartie at Vikings| accessdate=January 8, 2017| website=nj.com| author=Dan Duggan| date=September 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|URL=https://article.wn.com/view/2016/10/16/Giants_CB_Eli_Apple_wont_play_against_Ravens_Inactives_analy/| title=Giant's CB Eli Apple won't play against Ravens-Inactives analysis| accessdate=January 8, 2017| website=article.wn.com}}</ref> On November 7, 2016, he started his second game in a row and made four solo tackles against the [[2016 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] but was benched in favor of [[Trevin Wade]] as the Giants won 28\u201323.<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.nyg.247sports.com/Bolt/Steve-Spagnuolo-We-havent-lost-confidence-in-Eli-Apple-48959857/Amp|title=Steve Spagnuolo: We haven't lost confidence in Eli Apple|accessdate=November 15, 2016|author=Dan Schneider|website=www.nyg.247sports.com|date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> On November 14, 2016, Apple started his first game at outside corner, with Rodgers-Cromartie covering the slot and made one solo tackle in a 21\u201320 victory over the [[2016 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.nj.com/articles/19763966/why_is_giants_rookie_cb_eli_apple_playing_over_dom.amp| title=Why is Giant's rookie CB Eli Apple playing over Dominique Rodgers-Cromartie| accessdate=January 8, 2017| website=nj.com| author=Dan Duggan| date=December 2, 2016}}</ref> In Week 11, Apple collected a season-high nine combined tackles in a 22\u201316 victory over the [[2016 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]]. On December 4, 2016, Apple recorded five combined tackles, broke up two passes, recovered a fumble, and made his first career interception in the Giants\u2019 24\u201314 loss at the [[2016 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] in Week 13. Apple intercepted a pass attempt by Steelers\u2019 quarterback [[Ben Roethlisberger]], that was originally intended for wide receiver [[Eli Rogers]], during the third quarter.<ref>{{cite web |title=New York Giants at Pittsburgh Steelers - December 4th, 2016 |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201612040pit.htm |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=pro-football-reference.com}}</ref> Apple started the last ten games of the season and finished his rookie season in [[2016 NFL season|2016]] with 51 combined tackles (41 solo), seven pass deflections, one interception, and a forced fumble in 14 games and 11 starts.<ref name=\"NFL\">{{cite web|URL=http://www.nfl.com/player/eliapple/2555277/profile|title=NFL Player Profile: Eli Apple|accessdate=November 15, 2016|website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n====2017====\nApple entered training camp slated as a starting outside cornerback. Head coach Ben McAdoo named Apple and Janoris Jenkins the starting outside cornerbacks to begin the regular season with Dominique Rodgers-Cromartie as the starting slot cornerback.<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/200/NYG| title=Ourlads.com: New York Giant's depth chart: 10/01/2017| accessdate=October 17, 2017| website=ourlads.com}}</ref>\n\nHe started the Giant's season-opening 19\u20133 loss to the [[2017 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] and made seven combined tackles and a pass deflection. Apple was benched for the majority of the Giants\u2019 Week 5 loss to the [[2017 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]] due to disciplinary reasons. On October 15, 2017, Apple recorded five solo tackles and a career-high three pass deflections, helping the Giants gain their first victory of the season over the [[2017 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]]. Apple was heavily criticized by the New York Giants\u2019 coaching staff for his performance during their Week 10 loss at the [[2017 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]]. As a result of his performance, Apple was benched as a healthy scratch for the next four games (Weeks 11\u201314). On December 4, 2017, the New York Giants fired head coach [[Ben McAdoo]] after they fell to a 2\u201310 record. Defensive coordinator [[Steve Spagnuolo]] was named the interim head coach for the last four games.<ref>{{cite web |title=New York Giants fire coach Ben McAdoo after 2-10 start |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000887801/article/new-york-giants-fire-coach-ben-mcadoo-after-210-start |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=NFL.com |author=Patra, Kevin |date=December 4, 2017}}</ref> In Week 14, Apple was disciplined after posting on [[Twitter]] while on the sidelines of the Giants\u2019 Week 14 loss to the [[2017 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]]. He also aggravated teammates by posting a comment after the game which stated former Ohio State teammate and Dallas Cowboys\u2019 fullback [[Rod Smith (running back)|Rod Smith]] \u201ciced the New York Giants\u201d after scoring two touchdowns during the fourth quarter.<ref name=\"Collins\">{{cite web |title=Giants\u2019 Landon Collins apologizes for blasting teammate Eli Apple as \u2018a cancer\u2019 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2017/12/26/giants-landon-collins-blasts-teammate-eli-apple-as-a-cancer/ |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=December 27, 2017}}</ref> In Week 15, he returned as a backup cornerback and collected a season-high nine combined tackles during a 34\u201329 loss to the [[2017 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]].<ref name=\"NFL\"/>\n\nOn December 20, 2017, it was reported that tensions between Apple, and his teammates had reached an all-time high, with Giants\u2019 safety [[Landon Collins]] saying Apple was a \"cancer\" and should not be on the team in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/giants/index.ssf/2017/12/giants_landon_collins_claps_back_at_eli_apple_he_h.html|title=Landon Collins claps back at Eli Apple: 'He has to grow up'|publisher=|accessdate=October 23, 2018}}</ref> On December 27, 2017, Apple was suspended by the team for the 2017 season finale after reportedly getting into an argument with coaching staff about being asked to practice with the scout team and for a \"pattern of behavior that is conduct detrimental to the team\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Giants suspend CB Eli Apple|url=http://www.giants.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/Giants-suspend-CB-Eli-Apple/e34bc0b0-f6cc-4a73-9798-074a75a489b3|author=Eisen, Michael|website=Giants.com|date=December 27, 2017|access-date=December 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228061307/http://www.giants.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/Giants-suspend-CB-Eli-Apple/e34bc0b0-f6cc-4a73-9798-074a75a489b3|archive-date=December 28, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Apple finished the [[2017 NFL season]] with 49 combined tackles (41 solo) and eight pass deflections in 11 games and seven starts.<ref name=\"NFL\"/>\n\n====2018====\nThe Giant's new coach, [[Pat Shurmur]], said about Apple that he \"believe[d] in a clean slate\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Eli Apple has \u2018clean slate\u2019 with Pat Shurmur, Giants\u2019 new regime |url=https://www.newsday.com/sports/football/giants/giants-eli-apple-1.18661717 |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=newsday.com |date=May 21, 2018}}</ref> Apple was to be a starting cornerback  alongside safeties Landon Collins and [[Curtis Riley]].<ref>{{cite web |title=New York Giants depth chart: What the depth chart looks like after roster makeover |url=https://www.bigblueview.com/2018/9/6/17826844/new-york-giants-depth-chart-what-the-depth-chart-looks-like-after-roster-makeover |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=bigblueview.com |author=Valentine, Ed |date=September 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 16, 2018, Apple recorded one tackle before exiting in the third quarter of the Giants\u2019 20\u201313 loss at the [[2018 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] due to a [[groin]] injury.<ref>{{cite web |title=New York Giants C Jon Halapio, CB Eli Apple injured vs. Dallas Cowboys |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24706374/new-york-giants-c-jon-halapio-cb-eli-apple-injured-vs-dallas-cowboys |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |author=Raanan, Jordan |date=September 16, 2018}}</ref> His injury sidelined him for the next two games (Weeks 3\u20134).<ref>{{cite web |title=Giants injury report: Facing Saints without Eli Apple, Olivier Vernon |id= (3 starters among 5 out) |url= https://www.nj.com/giants/index.ssf/2018/09/giants_injury_report_facing_saints_without_eli_app.html |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=NJ.com |date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> In Week 6, he collected eight combined tackles and recorded a season-high three pass deflections during a 34\u201313 loss to the [[2018 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]].\n\n=== New Orleans Saints ===\nOn October 23, 2018, the New York Giants traded Apple to the [[New Orleans Saints]] for a fourth round pick in the [[2019 NFL Draft]] and a seventh round pick in the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Giants trade former first-round CB Eli Apple to Saints|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000977696/article/giants-trading-cornerback-eli-apple-to-saints|author=Patra, Kevin|website=NFL.com|date=October 23, 2018}}</ref> The New Orleans Saints traded for Apple in order to add him to their depleted secondary. Cornerback [[Patrick Robinson (cornerback)|Patrick Robinson]] was placed on injured reserve after breaking his ankle in Week 3 and cornerback [[Ken Crawley]] sustained an injury to his [[Abdominal internal oblique muscle|oblique]] the day before the trade.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saints' Ken Crawley: Will sit out Sunday |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/football/news/saints-ken-crawley-will-sit-out-sunday/ |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=CBSSports.com |date=October 28, 2018}}</ref> Head coach [[Sean Payton]] immediately named Apple a starting cornerback, reuniting him with former Ohio State secondary teammates [[Marshon Lattimore]] and [[Vonn Bell]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Instant analysis of Eli Apple trade: What it means, what it doesn't |url=https://saintswire.usatoday.com/2018/10/23/new-orleans-saints-new-york-giants-eli-apple-ken-crawley/ |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=saintswire.usatoday.com |author=Sigler, John |date=October 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn October 28, 2018, Apple made his New Orleans Saints\u2019 debut and collected nine solo tackles in a 30\u201320 win at the [[2018 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]] in Week 8.<ref>{{cite web |title=NFL Player stats: Eli Apple (2018) |url=http://www.nfl.com/player/eliapple/2555277/gamelogs?season=2018 |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> On November 11, 2018, Apple recorded his first interception with the Saints in a 51-14 victory over the [[Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nola.com/expo/sports/erry-2018/11/83f59a580b5519/8-takeaways-from-the-saints-51.html|title=8 takeaways from the Saints' 51-14 win against the Bengals|last=Duncan|first=Jeff|date=|work=NOLA.com|access-date=November 12, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn May 1, 2019, the Saints declined the fifth-year option on Apple's contract, making him a free agent in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saints declining CB Eli Apple's fifth-season option|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001029290/article/saints-declining-cb-eli-apples-fifthseason-option|author=Teope, Herbie|website=NFL.com|date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nApple was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania and was raised by his mother Annie Apple and stepfather Tim Apple in [[Voorhees Township, New Jersey]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mobile.philly.com/sports/?wss=/philly/sports/colleges/penn_state/&id=333077491&|title=Penn State game special for Ohio State's Eli Apple|accessdate=October 16, 2013|author=Erin McCarthey}}</ref> and in 2012 Apple changed his name from Eli Woodard to Eli Apple.<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.espn.com/blog/colleges/osu/insider/post?id=6342| title=Eli Woodard changes his name to Eli Apple| accessdate=January 5, 2017| website=ESPN.com| author=Brad Bournival| date=December 21, 2012}}</ref> He is the nephew of comedian [[Michael Blackson]]. During his true freshman year at Ohio State, issues with an iron deficiency limited Apple's play.<ref name=\"draft\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150325193022/http://www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/eli_apple_838099.html Ohio State Buckeyes bio]\n*[http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3040506 Profile] at ESPN.com\n\n{{2014 Ohio State Buckeyes football navbox}}\n{{2016 NFL Draft}}\n{{GiantsFirstPick}}\n{{Giants2016DraftPicks}}\n{{Las Vegas Raiders roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Apple, Eli}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Eastern Regional High School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Voorhees Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Camden County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes football players]]\n[[Category:New York Giants players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas Raiders players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}{{current sports transaction|sport=American football|trans=signing}}{{short description|American football cornerback}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Eli Apple\n| image               = Eli Apple.jpg\n| image_size          = 185\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Apple with the New York Giants in 2016\n| current_team        = Free agent\n| number              = \n| position            = [[Cornerback]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1995|8|9}}\n| birth_place         = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n| death_date          =\n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 1\n| weight_lbs          = 203\n| high_school         = [[Eastern Regional High School|Eastern Regional]]<br/>{{nowrap|([[Voorhees Township, New Jersey]])}}\n| college             = [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]]\n| draftyear           = 2016\n| draftround          = 1\n| draftpick           = 10\n| pastteams           = \n* [[New York Giants]] ({{NFL Year|2016}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2018}})\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] ({{NFL Year|2018}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2019}})\n| status              = \n|highlights=\n* [[Fiesta Bowl|Fiesta Bowl Champion]] ([[2016 Fiesta Bowl (January)|2016]])\n* [[College Football Playoff National Championship|CFP National Champion]] ([[2015 College Football Playoff National Championship|2015]])\n* [[Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl Champion]] ([[2015 Sugar Bowl|2015]])\n* [[Big Ten Football Championship Game|Big Ten Champion]] ([[2014 Big Ten Football Championship Game|2014]])\n* Defensive MVP of the [[2016 Fiesta Bowl (January)|2016 Fiesta Bowl]]\n|statleague=NFL\n|statweek=\n|statseason=2019\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n|statvalue1=233\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n|statvalue4=3\n|statlabel3=[[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n|statvalue3=4\n|statlabel2=[[Pass deflections]]\n|statvalue2=33\n|statlabel5=[[Interceptions]]\n|statvalue5=3\n|nfl=2555277\n}}\n\n'''Eli Apple''' (born August 9, 1995), formerly known as '''Eli Woodard''',<ref>{{cite news|title=College football recruiting 2013: Ohio State picks up top 2013 recruit in Eli Woodard|newspaper=Sporting News|date=May 15, 2012|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/ncaa-football/story/2012-02-16/ohio-state-buckeyes-recruiting-eli-woodard-urban-meyer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Eastern football star Eli Woodard picks Ohio State over Rutgers|date=February 16, 2012|newspaper=[[NJ.com]]|url=http://www.nj.com/hssports/blog/football/index.ssf/2012/02/eastern_football_star_eli_woodard_picks_ohio_state_over_rutgers.html}}</ref> is an [[American football]] [[cornerback]] who is a free agent. He played [[college football]] at [[Ohio State]], and was selected by the [[New York Giants]] with the 10th overall pick in the first round of the [[2016 NFL Draft]].\n\n==High school career==\nApple attended [[Eastern Regional High School]] in Voorhees, New Jersey and was teammates with [[Tennessee Titans]] [[Nickelback (gridiron football)|nickelback]] [[Logan Ryan]].  Apple was rated the top prospect in New Jersey in Rival's 2013 class and was ranked the 28th best prospect nationally. He received about twenty scholarship offers from [[University of Alabama|Alabama]], [[University of California|California]], [[Virginia Tech]], [[Boston College]], [[University of Wisconsin|Wisconsin]], [[University of Tennessee|Tennessee]], [[Purdue University|Purdue]], [[University of Miami|Miami]], [[Georgia Tech University|Georgia Tech]], [[University of Maryland|Maryland]], [[University of Michigan|Michigan]], [[University of Mississippi|Ole Miss]], [[University of Nebraska|Nebraska]], [[University of North Carolina|North Carolina]], [[North Carolina State University|NC State]], and [[Clemson University|Clemson]] and ranked his top three schools as [[Rutgers University|Rutgers]], [[Ohio State University|Ohio State]], and [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://n.rivals.com/content/prospects/9722| title=Rivals.com: Eli Apple| accessdate=January 5, 2017| website=n.rivals.com}}</ref> On February 12, 2012, he announced his verbal commitment to Ohio State after Rutgers head coach [[Greg Schiano]] left for the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.nj.com/articles/7749176/eastern_football_star_eli_woodard_picks_ohio_state_over_rutgers.amp| title=Eastern football star, Eli Woodard, picks Ohio State over Rutgers| accessdate=January 5, 2017| website=nj.com}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nApple enrolled at Ohio State in January 2013 as a five-star prospect (ESPN 150) and rated as high as the No. 11 prospect nationally on the ESPN 150. He was also rated as the No. 1 overall prospect in New Jersey and No. 6 cornerback prospect nationally by 247sports.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eli Apple Profile |publisher=Ohio State University |accessdate=March 24, 2015 |url=http://www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/eli_apple_838099.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150325193022/http://www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/eli_apple_838099.html |archivedate=March 25, 2015 }}</ref> He redshirted as a true freshman and went on to play in 2014 as a redshirt freshman.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ohio State football CB Eli Apple's transformation could stop Michigan from repeat passing success|publisher=The Plain Dealer, Cleveland, Ohio|date=November 25, 2014|url=http://www.cleveland.com/osu/index.ssf/2014/11/ohio_state_indiana_eli_apple_b.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Eli Apple making strides for Ohio State football |newspaper=The Lantern|date=October 17, 2014|url=http://thelantern.com/2014/10/eli-apple-making-strides-for-ohio-state-football/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ohio State football: Now healthy, Apple makes big impact at Nickelback|newspaper=The Columbus Dispatch|date=November 19, 2014|url=http://buckeyextra.dispatch.com/content/stories/2014/11/19/ohio-state-football-apple-11-19.html}}</ref> He played in the [[2015 Sugar Bowl]] and the [[2015 College Football Playoff National Championship]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Eastern\u2019s Eli Apple now a national champion with Ohio State Buckeyes |newspaper=Voorhees Sun|date=January 15, 2015|url=http://www.voorheessun.com/2015/01/15/easterns-eli-apple-now-national-champion-ohio-state-buckeyes/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=South Jersey's Eli Apple has a hand in Ohio State's Big Ten Championship shutout|newspaper=[[NJ.com]]|date=December 7, 2014|url=http://www.nj.com/rutgersfootball/index.ssf/2014/12/south_jerseys_eli_apple_has_a_hand_in_ohio_states_big_ten_championship_shutout.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Eastern High's Apple is 'fantastic' in Ohio State's victory|newspaper=Philadelphia Inquirer|date=January 15, 2015|url=http://articles.philly.com/2015-01-15/sports/58071036_1_marcus-mariota-oregon-coach-mark-helfrich-urban-meyer}}</ref> In his second season with the Buckeyes, he was the Defensive MVP.\n\n==Professional career==\n{{external media \n| video1 =\n[http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000639950/Eli-Apple-2016-Combine-Workout Eli Apple\u2019s NFL Combine Workout]\n| video2 =\n[http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000639940/Eli-Apple-40-yard-dash Eli Apple runs the 40-yard dash]\n| video3 =\n[http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000639991/Eli-Apple-makes-one-handed-grab-during-Combine-drills Eli Apple makes one-handed grab at combine]\n}}\nOn January 4, 2016, Apple announced his decision to forgo his remaining eligibility and enter the [[2016 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |title=NFL: Eastern grad Eli Apple declares for draft |url=https://www.courierpostonline.com/story/sports/nfl/2016/01/04/nfl-eastern-grad-eli-apple-declares-draft/78279316/ |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |newspaper=Courier Post| date=January 4, 2016}}</ref> Apple attended the [[NFL Scouting Combine]] and completed the majority of combine drills before suffering cramps.<ref>{{cite web |title=Combine confirmations: 11 prospects deserving of draft status |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000640478/article/combine-confirmations-11-prospects-deserving-of-draft-status |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=NFL.com |author=Reuter, Chad |date=March 1, 2016}}</ref> He finished with the tenth fastest time in the [[40-yard dash]] among all participating players at the NFL Combine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/top-performers#year=2016&workout=FORTY_YARD_DASH&position=QB-RB-WR-TE-S-DL-LB-CB-OL-SPEC|title=NFL Events: Combine Top Performers|website=www.nfl.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2016, Apple attended Ohio State\u2019s pro day, but opted to stand on his combine numbers and only performed the short shuttle, three-cone drill, and positional drills. Apple had pre-draft visits with multiple teams, including the [[Buffalo Bills]], [[San Francisco 49ers]], and [[Tennessee Titans]].<ref>{{cite web |title=49ers pre-draft visits tracker 2016: Who is on the radar? |url=https://www.ninersnation.com/2016/3/6/11162320/49ers-draft-visits-tracker-2016-workouts-combine-senior-bowl-shrine-game |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=ninersnation.com |author=Fucillo, David |date=April 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2016 NFL Draft: Tennessee Titans Draft Connections Tracker |url=https://www.musiccitymiracles.com/2016/4/4/11355248/2016-nfl-draft-tennessee-titans-draft-connections-tracker |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=musiccitymiracles.com |author=Lambert, Terry |date=April 4, 2016}}</ref> At the conclusion of the pre-draft process, Apple was projected to be an early to mid first round pick by NFL draft experts and scouts. He was ranked the third best cornerback prospect in the draft by DraftScout.com, was ranked the fourth best cornerback by NFL analyst [[Mike Mayock]], and was ranked the sixth best defensive back by [[Sports Illustrated]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=126576&draftyear=2016&genpos=CB| title=*Eli Apple, DS #3 CB, Ohio State: 2016 NFL Draft| accessdate=January 5, 2017| website=nfldraftscout.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2016 NFL Draft Position Rankings |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2016/04/12/nfl-draft-2016-position-rankings-players-prospects |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=si.com |author=Burke, Chris |date=April 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mike Mayock's 2016 NFL Draft position rankings 5.0 |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000656285/article/mike-mayocks-2016-nfl-draft-position-rankings-50 |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=NFL.com |author=Mike Mayock |date=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n{{external media\n| video1 =\n[http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000657045/Giants-pick-Eli-Apple-No-10 Giants draft Eli Apple 10th overall]\n| video2 =\n[http://www.nfl.com/videos/new-york-giants/0ap3000000657164/Highlights-Giants-draft-CB-Eli-Apple NFL Draft Profile: Eli Apple]\n}}\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 0\u215d\n|       weight = 199\n|         dash = 4.40\n|    ten split = 1.53\n| twenty split = 2.59\n|      shuttle = 4.08\n|   cone drill = 7.00\n|     vertical = \n|     broad ft = \n|     broad in = \n|        bench = 13\n|    wonderlic = 21<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/eli-apple-ohio-state-anonymous-scout-042716|title=Eli Apple's mom responds after anonymous NFL scout disses her son|first=Aaron|last=Torres|date=April 27, 2016|accessdate=July 16, 2016|work=[[FoxSports.com]]}}</ref>\n|     arm span = 31\u215c\n|    hand span = 9\u215c\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]/Ohio State's Pro Day<ref name=\"draft\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/2016/profiles/eli-apple?id=2555277|title=NFL Events: Combine Player Profiles \u2013 Eli Apple|publisher=NFL.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===New York Giants===\nThe [[New York Giants]] selected Apple in the first round (10th overall) of the [[2016 NFL Draft]]. Apple was the second cornerback drafted in 2016, after [[Jalen Ramsey]] (5th overall).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.giants.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/New-York-Giants-Draft-Ohio-State-CB-Eli-Apple-in-first-round/2cd6e721-1696-42e9-8b29-ca363dc2c72d |title=New York Giants Draft Ohio State CB Eli Apple in first round |last=Salomone |first=Dan |date=April 29, 2016 |website=Giants.com |accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref> It was reported that the New York Giants has initially planned to draft linebacker [[Leonard Floyd]] or offensive tackle [[Jack Conklin]]. However, circumstances changed after [[Laremy Tunsil]] unexpectedly fell out of the top ten. The [[Tennessee Titans]] traded ahead of the Giants to draft Jack Conklin (8th overall) and the [[Chicago Bears]] traded ahead of the Giants to select Leonard Floyd (9th overall). New York Giants\u2019 General Manager [[Jerry Reese]] opted to keep the tenth overall pick and selected Apple who was their highest graded player available on their draft board without any issues or injuries.<ref>{{cite web |title=The bizarre circumstances that led to the Giants drafting Eli Apple |url=https://www.sny.tv/giants/news/the-bizarre-circumstances-that-led-to-the-giants-drafting-eli-apple/264057636 |accessdate=November 5, 2018 |website=sny.tv |date=December 27, 2017}}</ref> Draft analysts and fans criticized the selection of Apple as many deemed it to be a reach.<ref>{{cite web |title=Giants GM blasts draft critics bashing Eli Apple pick |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000659672/article/giants-gm-blasts-draft-critics-bashing-eli-apple-pick |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=NFL.com |author=Patra, Kevin |date=May 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Giants select Ohio State CB Eli Apple in first round |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/new-york-giants/post/_/id/46512/giants-select-ohio-state-cb-eli-apple-in-first-round |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |author=Graziano, Dan |date=April 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2016====\nOn May 6, 2016, the New York Giants signed Apple to a fully guaranteed four year, $15.15 million that includes a signing bonus of $9.21 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.giants.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/Giants-sign-four-draft-picks--14-undrafted-free-agents/bce88848-ed81-4d6a-8e99-26f19049be9d |title=Giants sign four draft picks & 14 undrafted free agents |last=Eisen |first=Michael |date=May 6, 2016 |website=Giants.com |accessdate=July 16, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803005711/http://www.giants.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/Giants-sign-four-draft-picks--14-undrafted-free-agents/bce88848-ed81-4d6a-8e99-26f19049be9d |archive-date=August 3, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|URL=http://overthecap.com/player/eli-apple/4723/|title=Over the cap.com:Eli Apple contract|accessdate=November 15, 2016|website=overthecap.com}}</ref>\n\nApple entered training camp slated as the third cornerback on the depth chart behind veterans [[Janoris Jenkins]] and [[Dominique Rodgers-Cromartie]].  Head coach [[Ben McAdoo]] named Apple the third cornerback on the depth chart to begin the regular season and first-team nickelback.\n\nHe made his professional regular season debut in the [[2016 New York Giants season|New York Giants\u2019]] season-opener at the [[2016 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] and recorded four solo tackles during their 20\u201319 victory. On September 25, 2016, Apple earned his first career start and recorded one solo tackle in a 29\u201327 loss to the [[2016 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]], but left the game in the second quarter after suffering hamstring injury. Apple was inactive for the Giants\u2019 Week 4 loss at the [[2016 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]] with a hamstring injury. He was also sidelined for their Week 6 win against the [[2016 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] due to a groin injury.<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.nj.com/articles/19386255/giants_may_without_eli_apple_and_dominique_rodgers.amp| title=Giants may be with Eli Apple and Dominique Rodgers-Cromartie at Vikings| accessdate=January 8, 2017| website=nj.com| author=Dan Duggan| date=September 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|URL=https://article.wn.com/view/2016/10/16/Giants_CB_Eli_Apple_wont_play_against_Ravens_Inactives_analy/| title=Giant's CB Eli Apple won't play against Ravens-Inactives analysis| accessdate=January 8, 2017| website=article.wn.com}}</ref> On November 7, 2016, he started his second game in a row and made four solo tackles against the [[2016 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] but was benched in favor of [[Trevin Wade]] as the Giants won 28\u201323.<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.nyg.247sports.com/Bolt/Steve-Spagnuolo-We-havent-lost-confidence-in-Eli-Apple-48959857/Amp|title=Steve Spagnuolo: We haven't lost confidence in Eli Apple|accessdate=November 15, 2016|author=Dan Schneider|website=www.nyg.247sports.com|date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> On November 14, 2016, Apple started his first game at outside corner, with Rodgers-Cromartie covering the slot and made one solo tackle in a 21\u201320 victory over the [[2016 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.nj.com/articles/19763966/why_is_giants_rookie_cb_eli_apple_playing_over_dom.amp| title=Why is Giant's rookie CB Eli Apple playing over Dominique Rodgers-Cromartie| accessdate=January 8, 2017| website=nj.com| author=Dan Duggan| date=December 2, 2016}}</ref> In Week 11, Apple collected a season-high nine combined tackles in a 22\u201316 victory over the [[2016 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]]. On December 4, 2016, Apple recorded five combined tackles, broke up two passes, recovered a fumble, and made his first career interception in the Giants\u2019 24\u201314 loss at the [[2016 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] in Week 13. Apple intercepted a pass attempt by Steelers\u2019 quarterback [[Ben Roethlisberger]], that was originally intended for wide receiver [[Eli Rogers]], during the third quarter.<ref>{{cite web |title=New York Giants at Pittsburgh Steelers - December 4th, 2016 |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201612040pit.htm |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=pro-football-reference.com}}</ref> Apple started the last ten games of the season and finished his rookie season in [[2016 NFL season|2016]] with 51 combined tackles (41 solo), seven pass deflections, one interception, and a forced fumble in 14 games and 11 starts.<ref name=\"NFL\">{{cite web|URL=http://www.nfl.com/player/eliapple/2555277/profile|title=NFL Player Profile: Eli Apple|accessdate=November 15, 2016|website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n====2017====\nApple entered training camp slated as a starting outside cornerback. Head coach Ben McAdoo named Apple and Janoris Jenkins the starting outside cornerbacks to begin the regular season with Dominique Rodgers-Cromartie as the starting slot cornerback.<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/200/NYG| title=Ourlads.com: New York Giant's depth chart: 10/01/2017| accessdate=October 17, 2017| website=ourlads.com}}</ref>\n\nHe started the Giant's season-opening 19\u20133 loss to the [[2017 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] and made seven combined tackles and a pass deflection. Apple was benched for the majority of the Giants\u2019 Week 5 loss to the [[2017 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]] due to disciplinary reasons. On October 15, 2017, Apple recorded five solo tackles and a career-high three pass deflections, helping the Giants gain their first victory of the season over the [[2017 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]]. Apple was heavily criticized by the New York Giants\u2019 coaching staff for his performance during their Week 10 loss at the [[2017 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]]. As a result of his performance, Apple was benched as a healthy scratch for the next four games (Weeks 11\u201314). On December 4, 2017, the New York Giants fired head coach [[Ben McAdoo]] after they fell to a 2\u201310 record. Defensive coordinator [[Steve Spagnuolo]] was named the interim head coach for the last four games.<ref>{{cite web |title=New York Giants fire coach Ben McAdoo after 2-10 start |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000887801/article/new-york-giants-fire-coach-ben-mcadoo-after-210-start |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=NFL.com |author=Patra, Kevin |date=December 4, 2017}}</ref> In Week 14, Apple was disciplined after posting on [[Twitter]] while on the sidelines of the Giants\u2019 Week 14 loss to the [[2017 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]]. He also aggravated teammates by posting a comment after the game which stated former Ohio State teammate and Dallas Cowboys\u2019 fullback [[Rod Smith (running back)|Rod Smith]] \u201ciced the New York Giants\u201d after scoring two touchdowns during the fourth quarter.<ref name=\"Collins\">{{cite web |title=Giants\u2019 Landon Collins apologizes for blasting teammate Eli Apple as \u2018a cancer\u2019 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2017/12/26/giants-landon-collins-blasts-teammate-eli-apple-as-a-cancer/ |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=December 27, 2017}}</ref> In Week 15, he returned as a backup cornerback and collected a season-high nine combined tackles during a 34\u201329 loss to the [[2017 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]].<ref name=\"NFL\"/>\n\nOn December 20, 2017, it was reported that tensions between Apple, and his teammates had reached an all-time high, with Giants\u2019 safety [[Landon Collins]] saying Apple was a \"cancer\" and should not be on the team in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/giants/index.ssf/2017/12/giants_landon_collins_claps_back_at_eli_apple_he_h.html|title=Landon Collins claps back at Eli Apple: 'He has to grow up'|publisher=|accessdate=October 23, 2018}}</ref> On December 27, 2017, Apple was suspended by the team for the 2017 season finale after reportedly getting into an argument with coaching staff about being asked to practice with the scout team and for a \"pattern of behavior that is conduct detrimental to the team\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Giants suspend CB Eli Apple|url=http://www.giants.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/Giants-suspend-CB-Eli-Apple/e34bc0b0-f6cc-4a73-9798-074a75a489b3|author=Eisen, Michael|website=Giants.com|date=December 27, 2017|access-date=December 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228061307/http://www.giants.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/Giants-suspend-CB-Eli-Apple/e34bc0b0-f6cc-4a73-9798-074a75a489b3|archive-date=December 28, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Apple finished the [[2017 NFL season]] with 49 combined tackles (41 solo) and eight pass deflections in 11 games and seven starts.<ref name=\"NFL\"/>\n\n====2018====\nThe Giant's new coach, [[Pat Shurmur]], said about Apple that he \"believe[d] in a clean slate\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Eli Apple has \u2018clean slate\u2019 with Pat Shurmur, Giants\u2019 new regime |url=https://www.newsday.com/sports/football/giants/giants-eli-apple-1.18661717 |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=newsday.com |date=May 21, 2018}}</ref> Apple was to be a starting cornerback  alongside safeties Landon Collins and [[Curtis Riley]].<ref>{{cite web |title=New York Giants depth chart: What the depth chart looks like after roster makeover |url=https://www.bigblueview.com/2018/9/6/17826844/new-york-giants-depth-chart-what-the-depth-chart-looks-like-after-roster-makeover |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=bigblueview.com |author=Valentine, Ed |date=September 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 16, 2018, Apple recorded one tackle before exiting in the third quarter of the Giants\u2019 20\u201313 loss at the [[2018 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] due to a [[groin]] injury.<ref>{{cite web |title=New York Giants C Jon Halapio, CB Eli Apple injured vs. Dallas Cowboys |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24706374/new-york-giants-c-jon-halapio-cb-eli-apple-injured-vs-dallas-cowboys |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |author=Raanan, Jordan |date=September 16, 2018}}</ref> His injury sidelined him for the next two games (Weeks 3\u20134).<ref>{{cite web |title=Giants injury report: Facing Saints without Eli Apple, Olivier Vernon |id= (3 starters among 5 out) |url= https://www.nj.com/giants/index.ssf/2018/09/giants_injury_report_facing_saints_without_eli_app.html |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=NJ.com |date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> In Week 6, he collected eight combined tackles and recorded a season-high three pass deflections during a 34\u201313 loss to the [[2018 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]].\n\n=== New Orleans Saints ===\nOn October 23, 2018, the New York Giants traded Apple to the [[New Orleans Saints]] for a fourth round pick in the [[2019 NFL Draft]] and a seventh round pick in the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Giants trade former first-round CB Eli Apple to Saints|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000977696/article/giants-trading-cornerback-eli-apple-to-saints|author=Patra, Kevin|website=NFL.com|date=October 23, 2018}}</ref> The New Orleans Saints traded for Apple in order to add him to their depleted secondary. Cornerback [[Patrick Robinson (cornerback)|Patrick Robinson]] was placed on injured reserve after breaking his ankle in Week 3 and cornerback [[Ken Crawley]] sustained an injury to his [[Abdominal internal oblique muscle|oblique]] the day before the trade.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saints' Ken Crawley: Will sit out Sunday |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/football/news/saints-ken-crawley-will-sit-out-sunday/ |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=CBSSports.com |date=October 28, 2018}}</ref> Head coach [[Sean Payton]] immediately named Apple a starting cornerback, reuniting him with former Ohio State secondary teammates [[Marshon Lattimore]] and [[Vonn Bell]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Instant analysis of Eli Apple trade: What it means, what it doesn't |url=https://saintswire.usatoday.com/2018/10/23/new-orleans-saints-new-york-giants-eli-apple-ken-crawley/ |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=saintswire.usatoday.com |author=Sigler, John |date=October 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn October 28, 2018, Apple made his New Orleans Saints\u2019 debut and collected nine solo tackles in a 30\u201320 win at the [[2018 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]] in Week 8.<ref>{{cite web |title=NFL Player stats: Eli Apple (2018) |url=http://www.nfl.com/player/eliapple/2555277/gamelogs?season=2018 |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> On November 11, 2018, Apple recorded his first interception with the Saints in a 51-14 victory over the [[Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nola.com/expo/sports/erry-2018/11/83f59a580b5519/8-takeaways-from-the-saints-51.html|title=8 takeaways from the Saints' 51-14 win against the Bengals|last=Duncan|first=Jeff|date=|work=NOLA.com|access-date=November 12, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn May 1, 2019, the Saints declined the fifth-year option on Apple's contract, making him a free agent in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saints declining CB Eli Apple's fifth-season option|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001029290/article/saints-declining-cb-eli-apples-fifthseason-option|author=Teope, Herbie|website=NFL.com|date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nApple was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania and was raised by his mother Annie Apple and stepfather Tim Apple in [[Voorhees Township, New Jersey]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mobile.philly.com/sports/?wss=/philly/sports/colleges/penn_state/&id=333077491&|title=Penn State game special for Ohio State's Eli Apple|accessdate=October 16, 2013|author=Erin McCarthey}}</ref> and in 2012 Apple changed his name from Eli Woodard to Eli Apple.<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.espn.com/blog/colleges/osu/insider/post?id=6342| title=Eli Woodard changes his name to Eli Apple| accessdate=January 5, 2017| website=ESPN.com| author=Brad Bournival| date=December 21, 2012}}</ref> He is the nephew of comedian [[Michael Blackson]]. During his true freshman year at Ohio State, issues with an iron deficiency limited Apple's play.<ref name=\"draft\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150325193022/http://www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/eli_apple_838099.html Ohio State Buckeyes bio]\n*[http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3040506 Profile] at ESPN.com\n\n{{2014 Ohio State Buckeyes football navbox}}\n{{2016 NFL Draft}}\n{{GiantsFirstPick}}\n{{Giants2016DraftPicks}}\n{{Las Vegas Raiders roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Apple, Eli}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Eastern Regional High School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Voorhees Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Camden County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes football players]]\n[[Category:New York Giants players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas Raiders players]]\n", "name_user": "Rockchalk717", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eli_Apple"}
{"title_page": "Knee replacement", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox medical intervention \n|  Name        = Knee replacement \n| synonyms     = Knee arthroplasty\n|  Image       = Knee Replacement.png\n|  Caption     = Knee replacement\n|  ICD10       = 0SRD0JZ \n|  ICD9        = {{ICD9proc|81.54}} \n|  MeshID      = D019645 \n|  OPS301      = \n|  OtherCodes  = \n|  MedlinePlus = 002974 \n|  eMedicine   = 1250275\n}}\n\n'''Knee replacement''', also known as '''knee [[arthroplasty]]''', is a surgical procedure to replace the weight-bearing surfaces of the knee joint to relieve pain and disability. It is most commonly performed for [[osteoarthritis]],<ref name=\"Palmer\">{{cite journal\n| title =Total Knee Arthroplasty\n| journal =Medscape Reference\n| date = 27 June 2012\n| author =Simon H Palmer\n| volume =\n| issue =\n| pages =\n| url = http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/1250275-overview#showall\n| doi =\n| pmid =\n| pmc =\n}}</ref> and also for other knee diseases such as [[rheumatoid arthritis]] and [[psoriatic arthritis]]. In patients with severe deformity from advanced rheumatoid [[arthritis]], trauma, or long-standing osteoarthritis, the surgery may be more complicated and carry higher risk. [[Osteoporosis]] does not typically cause knee pain, deformity, or inflammation and is not a reason to perform knee replacement\n\nOther major causes of debilitating pain include meniscus tears, cartilage defects, and ligament tears. Debilitating pain from osteoarthritis is much more common in the elderly.\n\nKnee replacement surgery can be performed as a partial or a total knee replacement.<ref name=\"AAOS\">\n{{cite web\n | url = http://orthoinfo.aaos.org/topic.cfm?topic=A00389\n | title = Total Knee Replacement\n | date = December 2011\n | publisher  = American Academy of Orthopedic Surgeons\n | accessdate = \n}}</ref> In general, the surgery consists of replacing the diseased or damaged joint surfaces of the knee with metal and plastic components shaped to allow continued motion of the knee.\n\nThe operation typically involves substantial postoperative pain, and includes vigorous physical rehabilitation. The recovery period may be 12 weeks or longer and may involve the use of mobility aids (e.g. walking frames, canes, crutches) to enable the patient's return to preoperative mobility.<ref name=Leopold09>{{cite journal | pmid = 19387017 | doi=10.1056/NEJMct0806027 | volume=360 | issue=17 | title=Minimally invasive total knee arthroplasty for osteoarthritis |date=April 2009 | author=Leopold SS | journal=N. Engl. J. Med. | pages=1749\u201358}}</ref> It is estimated that approximately 82% of total knee replacements will last 25 years.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Evans|first=Jonathan T|last2=Walker|first2=Robert W|last3=Evans|first3=Jonathan P|last4=Blom|first4=Ashley W|last5=Sayers|first5=Adrian|last6=Whitehouse|first6=Michael R|date=February 2019|title=How long does a knee replacement last? A systematic review and meta-analysis of case series and national registry reports with more than 15 years of follow-up|journal=The Lancet|language=en|volume=393|issue=10172|pages=655\u2013663|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(18)32531-5|pmid=30782341|pmc=6381229}}</ref>\n\n==Medical uses==\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = horizontal\n   | footer    = X-ray of total knee replacement, anteroposterior view (left) and lateral view (right)\n   | image1    = Postoperative X-ray of normal knee prosthesis, anteroposterior view.jpg\n   | alt1      = \n   | caption1  = \n   | width1     = 150\n   | image2    = Postoperative X-ray of normal knee prosthesis, lateral view.jpg\n   | alt2      =\n   | caption2  = \n   | width2     = 170}}\n[[Image:Knee Replacement.jpg|thumb|The incision for knee replacement surgery]]\n\nKnee replacement surgery is most commonly performed in people with advanced [[osteoarthritis]] and should be considered when conservative treatments have been exhausted.<ref name=\"Management\">{{cite journal|last1=Van Manen|first1=MD|last2=Nace|first2=J|last3=Mont|first3=MA|title=Management of primary knee osteoarthritis and indications for total knee arthroplasty for general practitioners.|journal=The Journal of the American Osteopathic Association|volume=112 |issue=11 |pages=709\u2013715 |date=November 2012 |pmid=23139341}}</ref> Total knee replacement is also an option to correct significant knee joint or bone trauma in young patients.  Similarly, total knee replacement can be performed to correct mild [[valgus deformity|valgus]] or [[varus deformity]]. Serious valgus or varus deformity should be corrected by [[osteotomy]]. [[Physical therapy]] has been shown to improve function and may delay or prevent the need for knee replacement. Pain is often noted when performing physical activities requiring a wide range of motion in the knee joint.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Deyle GD, Henderson NE, Matekel RL, Ryder MG, Garber MB, Allison SC |title=Effectiveness of manual physical therapy and exercise in osteoarthritis of the knee. A randomized, controlled trial |journal=Ann. Intern. Med. |volume=132 |issue=3 |pages=173\u201381 |date=February 2000 |pmid=10651597 |url=http://www.annals.org/article.aspx?volume=132&page=173 |doi=10.7326/0003-4819-132-3-200002010-00002}}</ref>\n\n==Pre-operative preparation==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" width=\"180px\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| [[File:HKA and HKS angles.jpg|70px]]\n| Angles commonly measured before knee replacement surgery:\n*Hip-knee-shaft angle (HKS)<ref name=cooke2007>{{cite journal|vauthors=Cooke TD, Sled EA, Scudamore RA | title=Frontal plane knee alignment: a call for standardized measurement. | journal=J Rheumatol | year= 2007 | volume= 34 | issue= 9 | pages= 1796\u2013801 | pmid=17787049 | doi= | pmc= }}</ref>\n*Hip-knee-ankle angle (HKA)<ref name=dahl2009>{{cite journal|last1=W-Dahl|first1=Annette|last2=Toksvig-Larsen|first2=S\u00f6ren|last3=Roos|first3=Ewa M|title=Association between knee alignment and knee pain in patients surgically treated for medial knee osteoarthritis by high tibial osteotomy. A one year follow-up study|journal=BMC Musculoskeletal Disorders|volume=10|issue=1|pages=154|year=2009|issn=1471-2474|doi=10.1186/1471-2474-10-154|pmid=19995425|pmc=2796991}}</ref>\n|}\n\nTo indicate knee replacement in case of [[osteoarthritis]], its [[radiographic classification of osteoarthritis|radiographic classification]] and severity of symptoms should both be substantial. Such radiography should consist of weightbearing [[projectional radiography|X-rays]] of both knees- AP, Lateral, and 30 degrees of flexion. AP and lateral views may not show joint space narrowing, but the 30 degree flexion view is most sensitive for narrowing. Full length projections are also used in order to adjust the prosthesis to provide a neutral angle for the distal lower extremity. Two angles used for this purpose are:\n*Hip-knee-shaft angle (HKS),<ref name=cooke2007/> an angle formed between a line through the longitudinal axis of the [[femur|femoral]] shaft and its mechanical axis, which is a line from the center of the [[femoral head]] to the intercondylar notch of the distal femur.<ref name=\"CherianKapadia2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Cherian|first1=Jeffrey J.|last2=Kapadia|first2=Bhaveen H.|last3=Banerjee|first3=Samik|last4=Jauregui|first4=Julio J.|last5=Issa|first5=Kimona|last6=Mont|first6=Michael A.|title=Mechanical, Anatomical, and Kinematic Axis in TKA: Concepts and Practical Applications|journal=Current Reviews in Musculoskeletal Medicine|volume=7|issue=2|year=2014|pages=89\u201395|issn=1935-973X|doi=10.1007/s12178-014-9218-y|pmid=24671469|pmc=4092202}}</ref>\n*Hip-knee-ankle angle (HKA),<ref name=\"dahl2009\"/> which is an angle between the femoral mechanical axis and the center of the [[ankle joint]].<ref name=\"CherianKapadia2014\"/> It is normally between 1.0\u00b0 and 1.5\u00b0 of varus in adults.<ref name=\"SheehyFelson2011\">{{cite journal|last1=Sheehy|first1=L.|last2=Felson|first2=D.|last3=Zhang|first3=Y.|last4=Niu|first4=J.|last5=Lam|first5=Y.-M.|last6=Segal|first6=N.|last7=Lynch|first7=J.|last8=Cooke|first8=T.D.V.|title=Does measurement of the anatomic axis consistently predict hip-knee-ankle angle (HKA) for knee alignment studies in osteoarthritis? Analysis of long limb radiographs from the multicenter osteoarthritis (MOST) study|journal=Osteoarthritis and Cartilage|volume=19|issue=1|year=2011|pages=58\u201364|issn=10634584|doi=10.1016/j.joca.2010.09.011|pmid=20950695|pmc=3038654}}</ref>\n\nThe patient is to perform range of motion exercises and hip, knee and ankle strengthening as directed daily.  Before the surgery is performed, pre-operative tests are done: usually a [[complete blood count]], [[electrolytes]], [[APTT]] and [[Prothrombin time|PT]] to measure [[coagulation|blood clotting]], [[chest X-ray]]s, [[ECG]], and blood [[cross-matching]] for possible [[blood transfusion|transfusion]]. About a month before the surgery, the patient may be prescribed supplemental iron to boost the hemoglobin in their blood system. Accurate X-rays of the affected knee are needed to measure the size of components which will be needed. Medications such as [[warfarin]] and [[aspirin]] will be stopped some days before surgery to reduce the amount of bleeding. Patients may be admitted on the day of surgery if the pre-op work-up is done in the pre-[[anesthetic]] clinic or may come into [[hospital]] one or more days before surgery.  Currently there is insufficient quality evidence to support the use of pre-operative physiotherapy in older adults undergoing total knee arthroplasty.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chesham|first1=Ross Alexander|last2=Shanmugam|first2=Sivaramkumar|title=Does preoperative physiotherapy improve postoperative, patient-based outcomes in older adults who have undergone total knee arthroplasty? A systematic review|journal=Physiotherapy Theory and Practice|volume=33|issue=1|date=13 October 2016|pages=9\u201330|doi=10.1080/09593985.2016.1230660|pmid=27736286}}</ref>\n\nPreoperative education is currently an important part of patient care. There is some evidence that it may slightly reduce anxiety before knee replacement surgery, with low risk of detrimental effects.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McDonald|first=S|last2=Page|first2=MJ|last3=Beringer|first3=K|last4=Wasiak|first4=J|last5=Sprowson|first5=A|date=13 May 2014|title=Preoperative education for hip or knee replacement|url=|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=|issue=5|pages=CD003526|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD003526.pub3|pmid=24820247}}</ref>\n\n[[Bariatric surgery|Weight loss surgery]] before a knee replacement does not appear to change outcomes.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Smith|first1=TO|last2=Aboelmagd|first2=T|last3=Hing|first3=CB|last4=MacGregor|first4=A|title=Does bariatric surgery prior to total hip or knee arthroplasty reduce post-operative complications and improve clinical outcomes for obese patients? Systematic review and meta-analysis.|journal=The Bone & Joint Journal|date=September 2016|volume=98-B|issue=9|pages=1160\u20136|pmid=27587514|doi=10.1302/0301-620x.98b9.38024|url=https://ueaeprints.uea.ac.uk/58880/1/Bariatric_surgery_paper_ACCEPTED_10.05.2016.pdf}}<!--https://ueaeprints.uea.ac.uk/58880/1/Bariatric_surgery_paper_ACCEPTED_10.05.2016.pdf--></ref>\n\n==Technique==\n[[Image:Prothese-genou-IMG 0033.jpg|150px|thumb|left|Model of total knee replacement]]\nThe [[surgery]] involves exposure of the front of the knee, with detachment of part of the [[quadriceps muscle]] ([[vastus medialis]]) from the [[patella]].  The [[patella]] is displaced to one side of the joint, allowing exposure of the [[Anatomical terms of location|distal]] end of the [[femur]] and the [[Anatomical terms of location|proximal]] end of the [[tibia]]. The ends of these bones are then accurately cut to shape using cutting guides oriented to the long axis of the bones. The [[cartilage]]s and the [[anterior cruciate ligament]] are removed; the [[posterior cruciate ligament]] may also be removed but the [[medial collateral ligament|tibial]] and [[fibular collateral ligament|fibular]] collateral ligaments are preserved.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Verra|first=Wiebe C.|last2=van den Boom|first2=Lennard G. H.|last3=Jacobs|first3=Wilco|last4=Clement|first4=Darren J.|last5=Wymenga|first5=Ate A. B.|last6=Nelissen|first6=Rob G. H. H.|date=2013-10-11|title=Retention versus sacrifice of the posterior cruciate ligament in total knee arthroplasty for treating osteoarthritis|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|issue=10|pages=CD004803|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD004803.pub3|issn=1469-493X|pmc=6599815|pmid=24114343}}</ref> Whether the posterior cruciate ligament is removed or preserved depends on the type of implant used, although there appears to be no clear difference in knee function or range of motion favouring either approach.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Verra |first1=WC |last2=van den Boom |first2=LG |last3=Jacobs |first3=W |last4=Clement |first4=DJ |last5=Wymenga |first5=AA |last6=Nelissen |first6=RG |title=Retention versus sacrifice of the posterior cruciate ligament in total knee arthroplasty for treating osteoarthritis. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=11 October 2013 |issue=10 |pages=CD004803 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD004803.pub3 |pmid=24114343|pmc=6599815 }}</ref> Metal components are then impacted onto the bone or fixed using [[polymethylmethacrylate]] (PMMA) cement. Alternative techniques exist that affix the implant without cement.  These cement-less techniques may involve [[osseointegration]], including [[metal foam|porous metal]] prostheses. Finally, stability and range of motion is checked, followed by [[Therapeutic irrigation|irrigation]], [[hemostasis]], placement of hemovacs, and closure.<ref> [https://jomi.com/article/20/posterior-cruciate-retaining-total-knee-arthroplasty/] Scott MD R. Posterior cruciate-retaining total knee arthroplasty. J Med Ins. 2017;2017(20). doi:https://doi.org/10.24296/jomi/20</ref>\n\n===Femoral replacement===\nA round ended implant is used for the femur, mimicking the natural shape of the joint. On the tibia the component is flat, although it sometimes has a stem which goes down inside the bone for further stability. A flattened or slightly dished [[high-density polyethylene]] surface is then inserted onto the tibial component so that the weight is transferred metal to plastic not metal to metal. During the operation any deformities must be corrected, and the ligaments balanced so that the knee has a good range of movement and is stable and aligned. In some cases the articular surface of the patella is also removed and replaced by a polyethylene button cemented to the posterior surface of the patella.  In other cases, the patella is replaced unaltered.\n\n===Post-operative pain control===\nThe regional analgesia techniques (neuraxial anesthesia or continuous femoral nerve block<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Toftdahl|first1=K|last2=Nikolajsen|first2=L|last3=Haraldsted|first3=V|last4=Madsen|first4=F|last5=T\u00f8nnesen|first5=EK|last6=S\u00f8balle|first6=K|title=Comparison of peri- and intraarticular analgesia with femoral nerve block after total knee arthroplasty: a randomized clinical trial.|journal=Acta Orthopaedica|date=April 2007|volume=78|issue=2|pages=172\u20139|doi=10.1080/17453670710013645|pmid=17464603}}</ref> or adductor canal block) are used most commonly.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Practice guidelines for acute pain management in the perioperative setting: an updated report by the American Society of Anesthesiologists Task Force on Acute Pain Management|journal=Anesthesiology|volume=116|issue=2|pages=248\u2013273|doi=10.1097/ALN.0b013e31823c1030|pmid=22227789|date=February 2012|author1=American Society of Anesthesiologists Task Force on Acute Pain Management}}</ref> Local anesthesia infiltration in the pericapsular area using liposomal bupivacaine provides good analgesia in the post-operative period without increasing the risk for instability or nerve injury.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Essving|first1=P|last2=Axelsson|first2=K|last3=\u00c5berg|first3=E|last4=Sp\u00e4nnar|first4=H|last5=Gupta|first5=A|last6=Lundin|first6=A|title=Local infiltration analgesia versus intrathecal morphine for postoperative pain management after total knee arthroplasty: a randomized controlled trial.|journal=Anesthesia & Analgesia|date=October 2011|volume=113|issue=4|pages=926\u201333|doi=10.1213/ANE.0b013e3182288deb|pmid=21821506|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/eba9ed5e95c44f4ede12fc3890cbdd096a5cec69}}</ref> A combined approach of local infiltration analgesia and femoral nerve block to achieve multimodal analgesia is common.\n\n==Variations==\n{{medref|section|date=July 2019}}\n\nVariations in manufacture and surgical preparation for knee replacement occur between cemented and uncemented components, between resurfacing the patella or not, and between denervating the patella using electrocautery or not. Cemented-fixation may be more vulnerable to future aseptic loosening than the cement-less technique.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nakama|first=Gilberto Yoshinobu|last2=Peccin|first2=Maria Stella|last3=Almeida|first3=Gustavo JM|last4=Lira Neto|first4=Oz\u00f3rio de Almeida|last5=Queiroz|first5=Ant\u00f4nio AB|last6=Navarro|first6=Ricardo Dizioli|date=2012-10-17|title=Cemented, cementless or hybrid fixation options in total knee arthroplasty for osteoarthritis and other non-traumatic diseases|journal=Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=10|pages=CD006193|doi=10.1002/14651858.cd006193.pub2|pmid=23076921|issn=1465-1858}}</ref>\n\nRetaining the posterior cruciate ligament (PCL) has been shown to be beneficial for patients. Removal of the PCL has been shown to reduce the maximal force that the individual can place on that knee.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Mahoney OM, Noble PC, Rhoads DD, Alexander JW, Tullos HS |title=Posterior cruciate function following total knee arthroplasty. A biomechanical study |journal=J Arthroplasty |volume=9 |issue=6 |pages=569\u201378 |date=December 1994 |pmid=7699369 |doi=10.1016/0883-5403(94)90110-4}}</ref> Typically individuals who have the PCL removed will lean forward while climbing in order to maximize the force of the quadriceps. A variation in the total knee replacement procedure is to permit movement in the prostheses using a polyethylene insert, an approach called a mobile bearing total knee arthroplasty.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Hofstede|first=Stefanie N.|last2=Nouta|first2=Klaas Auke|last3=Jacobs|first3=Wilco|last4=van Hooff|first4=Miranda L.|last5=Wymenga|first5=Ate B.|last6=Pijls|first6=Bart G.|last7=Nelissen|first7=Rob G. H. H.|last8=Marang-van de Mheen|first8=Perla J.|date=2015|title=Mobile bearing vs fixed bearing prostheses for posterior cruciate retaining total knee arthroplasty for postoperative functional status in patients with osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis|url=|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=|issue=2|pages=CD003130|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD003130.pub3|issn=1469-493X|pmid=25650566}}</ref> There is no strong evidence that this approach improves knee function, mortality, number of adverse effects, or amount of pain compared to a fixed bearing approach for total knee replacement that retains the PCL.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n[[Minimally invasive procedure]]s have been developed in total knee replacement that do not cut the [[quadriceps tendon]]. There are different definitions of minimally invasive knee surgery, which may include a shorter incision length, retraction of the patella without eversion (rotating out), and specialized instruments. There are few randomized trials, but studies have found less postoperative pain, shorter hospital stays, and shorter recovery. However, no studies have shown long-term benefits.<ref name=Leopold09/>\n\n=== Partial knee replacement ===\n{{Main|Unicompartmental knee arthroplasty}}\nUnicompartmental arthroplasty (UKA), also called [[partial knee replacement]], is an option for some people. The knee is generally divided into three \"compartments\": ''medial'', ''lateral'', and ''patellofemoral''. Most people with arthritis severe enough to consider knee replacement have significant wear in two or more of the above compartments, and are treated with total knee replacement (TKA). A minority of people with osteoarthritis have wear primarily in one compartment, usually the medial, and may be candidates for unicompartmental knee replacement. Advantages of UKA compared to TKA include smaller incision, easier post-op rehabilitation, better postoperative range of motion, shorter hospital stay, less blood loss, lower risk of infection, stiffness, and [[blood clot]]s, but a harder revision if necessary. Persons with infectious or inflammatory arthritis ([[rheumatoid arthritis]], [[lupus erythematosus|lupus]], [[psoriasis]]), or marked deformity are not candidates for this procedure.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=U4u9BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA203&lpg=PA203&dq=partial+knee+replacement+Persons+with+infectious+or+inflammatory+arthritis+(rheumatoid+arthritis,+lupus,+psoriasis),+or+marked+deformity+are+not+candidates+for+this+procedure#v=onepage&q=partial%20knee%20replacement%20Persons%20with%20infectious%20or%20inflammatory%20arthritis%20(rheumatoid%20arthritis,%20lupus,%20psoriasis),%20or%20marked%20deformity%20are%20not%20candidates%20for%20this%20procedure&f=false|title=Design of Artificial Human Joints & Organs|last=Pal|first=Subrata|date=2013-08-31|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-1-4614-6255-2|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Components and zones==\n{{anchor|KS zones}}[[File:Knee prosthesis zones by Knee Society 2015, lateral view.jpg|thumb|150px|KS (Knee Society) zones, lateral view.<ref name=\"MeneghiniMont2015\">{{cite journal|last1=Meneghini|first1=R. Michael|last2=Mont|first2=Michael A.|last3=Backstein|first3=David B.|last4=Bourne|first4=Robert B.|last5=Dennis|first5=Doug A.|last6=Scuderi|first6=Giles R.|title=Development of a Modern Knee Society Radiographic Evaluation System and Methodology for Total Knee Arthroplasty|journal=The Journal of Arthroplasty|volume=30|issue=12|year=2015|pages=2311\u20132314|issn=08835403|doi=10.1016/j.arth.2015.05.049|pmid=26122112}}</ref>]]\n\nStandardized zones around the components are used for specifying for example signs of loosening on radiographic follow-up. There are various classification systems for specifying such zones,<ref name=\"NapierO\u2019Neill2018\">{{cite journal|last1=Napier|first1=Richard J.|last2=O\u2019Neill|first2=Christopher|last3=O\u2019Brien|first3=Seamus|last4=Doran|first4=Emer|last5=Mockford|first5=Brian|last6=Boldt|first6=Jens|last7=Beverland|first7=David E.|title=A prospective evaluation of a largely cementless total knee arthroplasty cohort without patellar resurfacing: 10-year outcomes and survivorship|journal=BMC Musculoskeletal Disorders|volume=19|issue=1|pages=205|year=2018|issn=1471-2474|doi=10.1186/s12891-018-2128-1|pmid=29945574|pmc=6020353}}</ref><ref name=\"KumarYadav2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Kumar|first1=Nishikant|last2=Yadav|first2=Chandrashekhar|last3=Raj|first3=Rishi|last4=Anand|first4=Sumit|title=How to Interpret Postoperative X-rays after Total Knee Arthroplasty|journal=Orthopaedic Surgery|volume=6|issue=3|year=2014|pages=179\u2013186|issn=17577853|doi=10.1111/os.12123|pmid=25179351|pmc=6583264}}</ref> including by KS (Knee Society) zones published in 2015.<ref name=\"MeneghiniMont2015\"/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"140\">\nFile:Knee prosthesis components.jpg|Main components of a knee prosthesis.\nFile:Knee prosthesis zones by Knee Society 2015, AP view.jpg|KS zones, anteroposterior (AP) view.<ref name=\"MeneghiniMont2015\"/>\n</gallery>\n\nSpecific KS zones are as follows, with * meaning that the zone can be specified as \"A\" (anterior), \"P\" (posterior), \"M\" (medial) or \"L\" (lateral):<ref name=\"MeneghiniMont2015\"/>\n*Femoral component (lateral view)\n:*Zone 1 and 2: Anterior and posterior flange, respectively.\n:*Zone 3: Central box/distal fixation region, where \"A\" and \"P\" designate the respective chamfers if visible*\n:*Zone 4: Stem extension*\n:*Zone 5: Stem\n*Tibial component:\n:*Zone 1: Anterior on lateral view, medial on anteroposterior (AP) view.\n:*Zone 2: Posterior on lateral view, lateral on AP view.\n:*Zone 3: Central keel/stem/peg fixation region*\n:*Zone 4: Stem extension*\n:*Zone 5: Inferior aspect of keel or stem\n\n==Risks==\n\nRisks and complications in knee replacement<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.vims.ac.in/healthcare/joint-replace-recovery-process.html | title=Knee Replacement Surgery in Bangalore - Vydehi Institute of Medical Sciences}}</ref> are similar to those associated with all [[Joint replacement#Risks and complications|joint replacements]]. The most serious complication is infection of the joint, which occurs in <1% of patients. Risk factors for infection are related to both patient and surgical factors.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tayton|first=E. R.|last2=Frampton|first2=C.|last3=Hooper|first3=G. J.|last4=Young|first4=S. W.|date=1 March 2016|title=The impact of patient and surgical factors on the rate of infection after primary total knee arthroplasty|journal=Bone Joint J|language=en|volume=98-B|issue=3|pages=334\u2013340|doi=10.1302/0301-620X.98B3.36775|issn=2049-4394|pmid=26920958|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/29599c765c5af3554b8517df19fb81f426261e88}}</ref> [[Deep vein thrombosis]] occurs in up to 15% of patients, and is symptomatic in 2\u20133%. Nerve injuries occur in 1\u20132% of patients. Persistent pain or stiffness occurs in 8\u201323% of patients. Prosthesis failure occurs in approximately 2% of patients at 5 years.<ref name=Leopold09/>\n\nThere is increased risk of complications for [[obese]] people going through total knee replacement.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kerkhoffs|first=GM|author2=Servien, E |author3=Dunn, W |author4=Dahm, D |author5=Bramer, JA |author6= Haverkamp, D |title=The influence of obesity on the complication rate and outcome of total knee arthroplasty: a meta-analysis and systematic literature review.|journal=The Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery. American Volume|date=17 October 2012|volume=94|issue=20|pages=1839\u201344|pmid=23079875|doi=10.2106/JBJS.K.00820|pmc=3489068}}</ref> The morbidly obese should be advised to lose weight before surgery and, if medically eligible, would probably benefit from [[bariatric surgery]].<ref>\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Samson AJ, Mercer GE, Campbell DG |title=Total knee replacement in the morbidly obese: a literature review |journal=ANZ J Surg |volume=80 |issue=9 |pages=595\u20139 |date=September 2010 |pmid=20840400 |doi=10.1111/j.1445-2197.2010.05396.x }}</ref>\n\nFracturing or chipping of the polyethylene platform between the femoral and tibial components may be of concern. These fragments may become lodged in the knee and create pain or may move to other parts of the body. Advancements in implant design have greatly reduced these issues but the potential for concern is still present over the lifespan of the knee replacement.\n\n===Deep vein thrombosis===\nAccording to the American Academy of Orthopedic Surgeons (AAOS), [[deep vein thrombosis]] in the leg is \"the most common complication of knee replacement surgery... prevention... may include periodic elevation of patient's legs, lower leg exercises to increase circulation, support stockings and medication to thin your blood.\"<ref name=\"AAOS\"/>\n\n===Fractures===\n[[Periprosthetic]] fractures are becoming more frequent with the aging patient population and can occur intraoperatively or postoperatively. Depending on the location of the fracture and the stability of the prosthesis, these can be treated surgically with open reduction and internal fixation or revision of the prosthesis.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n===Loss of motion===\nThe knee at times may not recover its normal range of motion (0\u2013135 degrees usually) after total knee replacement. Much of this is dependent on pre-operative function. Most patients can achieve 0\u2013110 degrees, but stiffness of the joint can occur. In some situations, manipulation of the knee under anesthetic is used to reduce post operative stiffness. There are also many implants from manufacturers that are designed to be \"high-flex\" knees, offering a greater range of motion.\n\n===Instability===\nIn some patients, the kneecap dislocates to the outer side of the knee after surgery. This is painful and usually needs to be treated by surgery to realign the kneecap. However, this is quite rare.\n\n===Loosening===\nLoosening of the prosthesis can be indicated on [[Projectional radiography|X-ray]] by thin radiolucenct spaces around the implant, or more obviously by implant displacement.<ref name=\"Cyteval2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Cyteval|first1=C.|title=Imaging of knee implants and related complications|journal=Diagnostic and Interventional Imaging|volume=97|issue=7\u20138|year=2016|pages=809\u2013821|issn=22115684|doi=10.1016/j.diii.2016.02.015|pmid=27423710}}</ref> \n\n===Infection===\nThe current classification of AAOS divides prosthetic infections into four types.<ref name=\"pmid16958480\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Leone JM, Hanssen AD |title=Management of infection at the site of a total knee arthroplasty |journal=Instr Course Lect |volume=55 |pages=449\u201361 |year=2006 |pmid=16958480 |doi=}}</ref>\n* Type 1 (positive intraoperative culture): Two positive intraoperative cultures\n* Type 2 (early postoperative infection): Infection occurring within first month after surgery\n* Type 3 (acute hematogenous infection): Hematogenous seeding of site of previously well-functioning prosthesis\n* Type 4 (late chronic infection): Chronic indolent clinical course; infection present for more than a month\n\nWhile it is relatively rare, periprosthetic infection remains one of the most challenging complications of joint arthroplasty.\nA detailed clinical history and physical remain the most reliable tool to recognize a potential periprosthetic infection. In some cases the classic signs of fever, chills, painful joint, and a draining sinus may be present, and diagnostic studies are simply done to confirm the diagnosis. In reality though, most patients do not present with those clinical signs, and in fact the clinical presentation may overlap with other complications such as aseptic loosening and pain. In those cases diagnostic tests can be useful in confirming or excluding infection.\n\n[[File:ProthesenlockerungPET-CT.jpg|thumb|FDG-PET CT showing septic loosening of knee prothesis; the FDG-enrichment shows entensive inflammatory foci: demonstrative: the PET-image ist unlike the CT reconstruction not disturbed by the high radiation attenuation of the prothesis.]]\n\nModern diagnosis of infection around a total knee replacement is based on the Musculoskeletal Infection Society (MSIS) criteria.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Parvizi|first1=Javad|last2=Zmistowski|first2=Benjamin|last3=Berbari|first3=Elie F.|last4=Bauer|first4=Thomas W.|last5=Springer|first5=Bryan D.|last6=Della Valle|first6=Craig J.|last7=Garvin|first7=Kevin L.|last8=Mont|first8=Michael A.|last9=Wongworawat|first9=Montri D.|last10=Zalavras|first10=Charalampos G.|title=New Definition for Periprosthetic Joint Infection: From the Workgroup of the Musculoskeletal Infection Society|journal=Clinical Orthopaedics and Related Research|date=22 September 2011|volume=469|issue=11|pages=2992\u20132994|doi=10.1007/s11999-011-2102-9|pmid=21938532|pmc=3183178}}</ref> They are:\n\n1. There is a sinus tract communicating with the prosthesis; or\n2. A pathogen is isolated by culture from at least two separate tissue or fluid samples obtained from the affected prosthetic joint; \nor\n\nFour of the following six criteria exist:\n\n1.Elevated serum erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR>30mm/hr) and serum C-reactive protein (CRP>10&nbsp;mg/L) concentration,\n\n2.Elevated synovial leukocyte count,\n\n3.Elevated synovial neutrophil percentage (PMN%),\n\n4.Presence of purulence in the affected joint,\n\n5.Isolation of a microorganism in one culture of periprosthetic tissue or fluid, or\n\n6. Greater than five neutrophils per high-power field in five high-power fields observed from histologic analysis of periprosthetic tissue at \u00d7400 magnification.\n\nNone of the above laboratory tests has 100% sensitivity or specificity for diagnosing infection. Specificity improves when the tests are performed in patients in whom clinical suspicion exists. ESR and CRP remain good 1st line tests for screening (high sensitivity, low specificity).  Aspiration of the joint remains the test with the highest specificity for confirming infection.\n\nThe choice of treatment depends on the type of prosthetic infection.<ref name=\"pmid10535593\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Segawa H, Tsukayama DT, Kyle RF, Becker DA, Gustilo RB |title=Infection after total knee arthroplasty. A retrospective study of the treatment of eighty-one infections |journal=J Bone Joint Surg Am |volume=81 |issue=10 |pages=1434\u201345 |year=1999 |pmid=10535593 |doi=10.2106/00004623-199910000-00008}}</ref>\n\n#Positive intraoperative cultures: Antibiotic therapy alone\n#Early post-operative infections: debridement, antibiotics, and retention of prosthesis.\n#Acute hematogenous infections: debridement, antibiotic therapy, retention of prosthesis.\n#Late chronic: delayed exchange arthroplasty. Surgical d\u00e9bridement and parenteral antibiotics alone in this group has limited success, and standard of care involves exchange arthroplasty.<ref name=\"pmid17438469\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Chiu FY, Chen CM |title=Surgical d\u00e9bridement and parenteral antibiotics in infected revision total knee arthroplasty |journal=Clin. Orthop. Relat. Res. |volume=461 |pages=130\u20135 |year=2007 |pmid=17438469 |doi=10.1097/BLO.0b013e318063e7f3}}</ref>\n\nAppropriate antibiotic doses can be found at the following instructional course lecture by AAOS<ref name=\"pmid16958480\"/>\n\n==Post-operative evaluation==\n[[File:X-ray of knee prosthesis with overhang, annotated.jpg|thumb|150px|Overhang (arrow) does not seem to have any detrimental effect.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Impact Of Tibial Component Overhang On Outcome Scores And Pain In Total Knee Replacement|date=2018-02-21|author=S.G.F. Abram, A.G Marsh, F. Nicol, A.S. Brydone, A. Mohammed, S.J. Spencer|journal=Orthopaedic Proceedings}}</ref>]]\nKnee replacement is routinely evaluated by [[Projectional radiograph|X-ray]], including the following measures:\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"380\">\nFile:X-ray of HKA angle with knee prosthesis.jpg|'''HKA''': Hip-knee-ankle angle, which is ideally between 3\u00b0 [[genu varum|varum]] to 3\u00b0 [[Genu valgum|valgum]] from a [[right angle]].<ref name=Inui2013>{{cite journal|last1=Inui|first1=Hiroshi|last2=Taketomi|first2=Shuji|last3=Nakamura|first3=Kensuke|last4=Takei|first4=Seira|last5=Takeda|first5=Hideki|last6=Tanaka|first6=Sakae|last7=Nakagawa|first7=Takumi|title=Influence of navigation system updates on total knee arthroplasty|journal=Sports Medicine, Arthroscopy, Rehabilitation, Therapy & Technology|volume=5|issue=1|pages=10|year=2013|issn=1758-2555|doi=10.1186/2052-1847-5-10|pmid=23638774|pmc=3653716}} [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0 (CC-BY-2.0)]</ref>\nFile:Postoperative X-ray of normal knee prosthesis, anteroposterior view, annotated.jpg|- '''FFC''': frontal femoral component angle. It is typically regarded as optimal when being 2\u20137\u00b0 in valgus.<ref name=\"GromovKorchi2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Gromov|first1=Kirill|last2=Korchi|first2=Mounim|last3=Thomsen|first3=Morten G|last4=Husted|first4=Henrik|last5=Troelsen|first5=Anders|title=What is the optimal alignment of the tibial and femoral components in knee arthroplasty?|journal=Acta Orthopaedica|volume=85|issue=5|year=2014|pages=480\u2013487|issn=1745-3674|doi=10.3109/17453674.2014.940573|pmid=25036719|pmc=4164865}}</ref><br>- '''FTC''': frontal tibial component angle, which is regarded as optimal when being at a [[right angle]]. A varus position of more than 3\u00b0 has generally been found to increase the failure rate of the prosthesis.<ref name=\"GromovKorchi2014\"/>\nFile:Postoperative X-ray of normal knee prosthesis, lateral view, annotated.jpg|- '''Anterior femoral notching''' (the femoral component causing reduced thickness of the distal femur anteriorly), seems to cause an increased risk of fractures when exceeding about 3 mm.<ref name=\"LeeWang2015\">{{cite journal|last1=Lee|first1=Ju Hong|last2=Wang|first2=Seong-Il|title=Risk of Anterior Femoral Notching in Navigated Total Knee Arthroplasty|journal=Clinics in Orthopedic Surgery|volume=7|issue=2|year=2015|pages=217\u201324|issn=2005-291X|doi=10.4055/cios.2015.7.2.217|pmid=26217469|pmc=4515463}}</ref><br>- '''LTC''': lateral (or sagittal) tibial component angle, which is ideally positioned so that the tibia is 0\u20137\u00b0 flexed compared to at a right angle with the tibial plate.<ref name=\"GromovKorchi2014\"/>\n</gallery>\n\n==Post-operative rehabilitation==\nThe length of post-operative hospitalization is 5 days on average depending on the health status of the patient and the amount of support available outside the hospital setting.<ref name=\"CarterPotts2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Carter|first1=Evelene M|last2=Potts|first2=Henry WW|title=Predicting length of stay from an electronic patient record system: a primary total knee replacement example|journal=BMC Medical Informatics and Decision Making|volume=14|issue=1|year=2014|pages=26|issn=1472-6947|doi=10.1186/1472-6947-14-26|pmid=24708853|pmc=3992140}}</ref> Protected [[weight bearing]] on crutches or a [[Walker (tool)|walker]] is required until specified by the surgeon<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.massgeneral.org/ortho-hip-knee/patient-education/pt-ed-kneerehab.pdf|title=Rehabilitation|last=|first=|date=|website=massgeneral.org|access-date=}}</ref> because of weakness in the quadriceps muscle<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Valtonen|first=Anu|last2=P\u00f6yh\u00f6nen|first2=Tapani|last3=Heinonen|first3=Ari|last4=Sipil\u00e4|first4=Sarianna|date=1 October 2009|title=Muscle Deficits Persist After Unilateral Knee Replacement and Have Implications for Rehabilitation|journal=Physical Therapy|language=en|volume=89|issue=10|pages=1072\u20131079|doi=10.2522/ptj.20070295|issn=0031-9023|pmid=19713269|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the immediate post-operative period, up to 39% of knee replacement patients experience inadequate pain control.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Michael M. H.|last2=Hartley|first2=Rebecca L.|last3=Leung|first3=Alexander A.|last4=Ronksley|first4=Paul E.|last5=Jett\u00e9|first5=Nathalie|last6=Casha|first6=Steven|last7=Riva-Cambrin|first7=Jay|date=2019-04-01|title=Preoperative predictors of poor acute postoperative pain control: a systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=BMJ Open|volume=9|issue=4|pages=e025091|doi=10.1136/bmjopen-2018-025091|issn=2044-6055|pmid=30940757|pmc=6500309}}</ref>\n\nTo increase the likelihood of a good outcome after surgery, multiple weeks of [[physical therapy]] is necessary. In these weeks, the therapist will help the patient return to normal activities, as well as prevent blood clots, improve circulation, increase range of motion, and eventually strengthen the surrounding muscles through specific exercises. Whether techniques such as [[neuromuscular electrical stimulation]] are effective at promoting gains in knee muscle strength after surgery are unclear.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Monaghan |first1=B |last2=Caulfield |first2=B |last3=O'Math\u00fana |first3=DP |title=Surface neuromuscular electrical stimulation for quadriceps strengthening pre and post total knee replacement. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=20 January 2010 |issue=1 |pages=CD007177 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD007177.pub2 |pmid=20091621|url=http://doras.dcu.ie/19651/1/dpom4.pdf }}</ref>\nOften range of motion (to the limits of the prosthesis) is recovered over the first two weeks (the earlier the better). Over time, patients are able to increase the amount of weight bearing on the operated leg, and eventually are able to tolerate full weight bearing with the guidance of the physical therapist.<ref name=\":0\" /> After about ten months, the patient should be able to return to normal daily activities, although the operated leg may be significantly weaker than the non-operated leg.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFor post-operative knee replacement patients, immobility is a factor precipitated by pain and other complications. Mobility is known as an important aspect of human biology that has many beneficial effects on the body system.<ref>Leah, 2013 {{full citation needed|date=April 2018}}</ref> It is well documented in literature that physical immobility affects every body system and contributes to functional complications of prolonged illness.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1097/cnq.0b013e3182750631| pmid = 23221435| title = Foreword| journal = Critical Care Nursing Quarterly| volume = 36| issue = 1| pages = 1\u20132| year = 2013| last1 = &Na| last2 = Dickinson| first2 = S}}</ref> In most medical-surgical hospital units that perform knee replacements, ambulation is a key aspect of nursing care that is promoted to patients. Early ambulation can decrease the risk of complications associated with immobilization such as pressure ulcers, deep vein thrombosis (DVT), impaired pulmonary function, and loss of functional mobility.<ref name=\"Teodoro, 2016\">Teodoro, 2016 {{full citation needed|date=April 2018}}</ref> Nurses\u2019 promotion and execution of early ambulation on patients has found that it greatly reduces the complications listed above, as well as decreases length of stay and costs associated with further hospitalization.<ref name=\"Teodoro, 2016\"/> Nurses may also work with teams such as physical therapy and occupational therapy to accomplish ambulation goals and reduce complications.<ref>Ong & Pua, 2011{{full citation needed|date=April 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Continuous passive motion]] (CPM) is a postoperative therapy approach that uses a machine to move the knee continuously through a specific range of motion, with the goal of preventing joint stiffness and improving recovery.<ref name=\"APTAfive\">{{Citation|title=Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question|date=15 September 2014|url=http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-physical-therapy-association/|author1=American Physical Therapy Association|author1-link=American Physical Therapy Association|work=[[Choosing Wisely]]: an initiative of the [[ABIM Foundation]]|page=|publisher=American Physical Therapy Association|accessdate=15 September 2014}} \n</ref><ref name=Harvey2014>{{Cite journal|last=Harvey|first=Lisa A.|last2=Brosseau|first2=Lucie|last3=Herbert|first3=Robert D.|date=2014-02-06|title=Continuous passive motion following total knee arthroplasty in people with arthritis|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/6c7a31933b39657ebe61c95a9ab4a4383aff5a13|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=|issue=2|pages=CD004260|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD004260.pub3|issn=1469-493X|pmid=24500904}}</ref> There is no evidence that CPM therapy leads to a clinically significant improvement in range of motion, pain, knee function, or quality of life.<ref name=Harvey2014 /> CPM is inexpensive, convenient, and assists patients in therapeutic compliance. However, CPM should be used in conjunction with traditional physical therapy.<ref name=\"APTAfive\"/> In unusual cases where the person has a problem which prevents standard mobilization treatment, then CPM may be useful.<ref name=\"APTAfive\"/>\n\n[[Cryotherapy]], also known as 'cold therapy' is sometimes recommended after surgery for pain relief and to limit swelling of the knee. Cryotherapy involves the application of ice bags or cooled water to the skin of the knee joint. However, the evidence that cryotherapy reduces pain and swelling is very weak and the benefits after total knee replacement surgery have been shown to be very small.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Adie |first1=S |last2=Kwan |first2=A |last3=Naylor |first3=JM |last4=Harris |first4=IA |last5=Mittal |first5=R |title=Cryotherapy following total knee replacement. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=12 September 2012 |issue=9 |pages=CD007911 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD007911.pub2 |pmid=22972114}}</ref>\n\nSome physicians and patients may consider having [[ultrasonography for deep venous thrombosis]] after knee replacement.<ref name=\"AAOSfive\">{{Citation |author1 = American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons |author1-link = American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons |date = February 2013 |title = Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question |publisher = American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons |work = [[Choosing Wisely]]: an initiative of the [[ABIM Foundation]] |page = |url = http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-academy-of-orthopaedic-surgeons/ |accessdate = 19 May 2013}}, which cites\n*{{cite journal |author=Members of 2007 and 2011 AAOS Guideline Development Work Groups on PE/VTED Prophylaxis |author2=Mont, M |author3=Jacobs, J |author4=Lieberman, J |author5=Parvizi, J |author6=Lachiewicz, P |author7=Johanson, N |author8= Watters, W  |title=Preventing venous thromboembolic disease in patients undergoing elective total hip and knee arthroplasty. |journal=The Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery. American Volume |date=18 April 2012 |volume=94 |issue=8 |pages=673\u20134 |pmid=22517384 |doi=10.2106/JBJS.9408edit |pmc=3326687}}</ref> However, this kind of screening should be done only when indicated because to perform it routinely would be [[unnecessary health care]].<ref name=\"AAOSfive\"/> If a medical condition exists that could cause deep vein thrombosis, a physician can choose to treat patients with [[cryotherapy]] and [[intermittent pneumatic compression]] as a preventive measure.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nNeither [[gabapentin]] nor [[pregabalin]] have been found to be useful for pain following a knee replacement.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hamilton|first1=TW|last2=Strickland|first2=LH|last3=Pandit|first3=HG|title=A Meta-Analysis on the Use of Gabapentinoids for the Treatment of Acute Postoperative Pain Following Total Knee Arthroplasty.|journal=The Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery. American Volume|date=17 August 2016|volume=98|issue=16|pages=1340\u201350|pmid=27535436|doi=10.2106/jbjs.15.01202}}</ref> A Cochrane review concluded that early multidisciplinary rehabilitation programs may produce better results at the rate of activity and participation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Khan|first=Fary|last2=Ng|first2=Louisa|last3=Gonzalez|first3=Senen|last4=Hale|first4=Tom|last5=Turner-Stokes|first5=Lynne|date=2008-04-23|title=Multidisciplinary rehabilitation programmes following joint replacement at the hip and knee in chronic arthropathy|journal=Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|issue=2|pages=CD004957|doi=10.1002/14651858.cd004957.pub3|pmid=18425906|issn=1465-1858}}</ref>\n\n==Frequency==\n\nWith 718,000 hospitalizations, knee arthroplasty accounted for 4.6% of all United States operating room procedures in 2011\u2014making it one of the most common procedures performed during hospital stays.<ref name=\"hcup-us.ahrq.gov\">Pfuntner A., Wier L.M., Stocks C. Most Frequent Procedures Performed in U.S. Hospitals, 2011. HCUP Statistical Brief #165. October 2013. Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality, Rockville, MD. [http://www.hcup-us.ahrq.gov/reports/statbriefs/sb165.jsp].</ref><ref>{{cite web |vauthors=Weiss AJ, Elixhauser A, Andrews RM | title = Characteristics of Operating Room Procedures in U.S. Hospitals, 2011. | work = HCUP Statistical Brief #170 | publisher = Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality | location = Rockville, MD | date = February 2014 | url = http://hcup-us.ahrq.gov/reports/statbriefs/sb170-Operating-Room-Procedures-United-States-2011.jsp }}</ref>  The number of knee arthroplasty procedures performed in U.S. hospitals increased 93% between 2001 and 2011.<ref>{{cite web |vauthors=Weiss AJ, Elixhauser A | title = Trends in Operating Room Procedures in U.S. Hospitals, 2001\u20142011. | work = HCUP Statistical Brief #171 | publisher = Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality | location = Rockville, MD | date = March 2014 | url = http://hcup-us.ahrq.gov/reports/statbriefs/sb171-Operating-Room-Procedure-Trends.jsp }}</ref> A study of United States community hospitals showed that in 2012, among hospitalizations that involved an OR procedure, knee arthroplasty was the OR procedure performed most frequently during hospital stays paid by Medicare (10.8 percent of stays) and by private insurance (9.1 percent). Knee arthroplasty was not among the top five most frequently performed OR procedures for stays paid by Medicaid or for uninsured stays.<ref>{{cite web |vauthors=Fingar KR, Stocks C, Weiss AJ, Steiner CA | title =  Most Frequent Operating Room Procedures Performed in U.S. Hospitals, 2003-2012 | work = HCUP Statistical Brief #186 | publisher = Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality | location = Rockville, MD | date = December 2014 | url =https://www.hcup-us.ahrq.gov/reports/statbriefs/sb186-Operating-Room-Procedures-United-States-2012.jsp}}</ref>\n\nBy 2030, the demand for primary total knee arthroplasty is projected to increase to 3.48 million surgeries performed annually in the U.S.<ref>{{cite journal | year = 2013 | title =  Essential amino acid supplementation in patients following total knee arthroplasty| journal = J Clin Invest | volume = 123 | issue = 11| pages = 4654\u20134666 | doi = 10.1172/JCI70160 | pmid=24135139 | pmc=3809795 |vauthors=Dreyer HC, Strycker LA, Senesac HA, Hocker AD, Smolkowski K, Shah SN, Jewett BA }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Autologous chondrocyte implantation]]\n* [[Microfracture surgery]]\n* [[Knee osteoarthritis]]\n* [[Osseointegration]]\n* [[Meniscus transplant]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/08/health/08brod.html A New Set of Knees Comes at a Price: A Whole Lot of Pain] By Jane E. Brody, The New York Times, 8 February 2005\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/15/health/15brod.html When It Comes to Severe Pain, Doctors Still Have Much to Learn] By Jane E. Brody, The New York Times, 15 February 2005\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/20/health/20brod.html A Year With My New Knees: Much Pain but Much Gain] By Jane E. Brody, The New York Times, 20 December 2005\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/03/health/03brod.html 3 Years Later, Knees Made for Dancing], By Jane E. Brody, The New York Times, 3 June 2008\n*[http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/09/relief-for-joints-besieged-by-arthritis/ Relief for Joints Besieged by Arthritis], By Jane E. Brody, The New York Times, 9 July 2012\n{{Medical resources}}\n{{Operations and other procedures on the musculoskeletal system}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knee Replacement}}\n[[Category:Implants (medicine)]]\n[[Category:Prosthetics]]\n[[Category:Orthopedic surgical procedures]]\n[[Category:Knee treatments|Replacement]]\n[[Category:Orthopedic implants]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox medical intervention \n|  Name        = Knee replacement \n| synonyms     = Knee arthroplasty\n|  Image       = Knee Replacement.png\n|  Caption     = Knee replacement\n|  ICD10       = 0SRD0JZ \n|  ICD9        = {{ICD9proc|81.54}} \n|  MeshID      = D019645 \n|  OPS301      = \n|  OtherCodes  = \n|  MedlinePlus = 002974 \n|  eMedicine   = 1250275\n}}\n\n'''Knee replacement''', also known as '''knee [[arthroplasty]]''', is a surgical procedure to replace the weight-bearing surfaces of the knee joint to relieve pain and disability. It is most commonly performed for [[osteoarthritis]],<ref name=\"Palmer\">{{cite journal\n| title =Total Knee Arthroplasty\n| journal =Medscape Reference\n| date = 27 June 2012\n| author =Simon H Palmer\n| volume =\n| issue =\n| pages =\n| url = http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/1250275-overview#showall\n| doi =\n| pmid =\n| pmc =\n}}</ref> and also for other knee diseases such as [[rheumatoid arthritis]] and [[psoriatic arthritis]]. In patients with severe deformity from advanced rheumatoid [[arthritis]], trauma, or long-standing osteoarthritis, the surgery may be more complicated and carry higher risk. [[Osteoporosis]] does not typically cause knee pain, deformity, or inflammation and is not a reason to perform knee replacement\n\nOther major causes of debilitating pain include meniscus tears, cartilage defects, and ligament tears. Debilitating pain from osteoarthritis is much more common in the elderly.\n\nKnee replacement surgery can be performed as a partial or a total knee replacement.<ref name=\"AAOS\">\n{{cite web\n | url = http://orthoinfo.aaos.org/topic.cfm?topic=A00389\n | title = Total Knee Replacement\n | date = December 2011\n | publisher  = American Academy of Orthopedic Surgeons\n | accessdate = \n}}</ref> In general, the surgery consists of replacing the diseased or damaged joint surfaces of the knee with metal and plastic components shaped to allow continued motion of the knee.\n\nThe operation typically involves substantial postoperative pain, and includes vigorous physical rehabilitation. The recovery period may be 12 weeks or longer and may involve the use of mobility aids (e.g. walking frames, canes, crutches) to enable the patient's return to preoperative mobility.<ref name=Leopold09>{{cite journal | pmid = 19387017 | doi=10.1056/NEJMct0806027 | volume=360 | issue=17 | title=Minimally invasive total knee arthroplasty for osteoarthritis |date=April 2009 | author=Leopold SS | journal=N. Engl. J. Med. | pages=1749\u201358}}</ref> It is estimated that approximately 82% of total knee replacements will last 25 years.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Evans|first=Jonathan T|last2=Walker|first2=Robert W|last3=Evans|first3=Jonathan P|last4=Blom|first4=Ashley W|last5=Sayers|first5=Adrian|last6=Whitehouse|first6=Michael R|date=February 2019|title=How long does a knee replacement last? A systematic review and meta-analysis of case series and national registry reports with more than 15 years of follow-up|journal=The Lancet|language=en|volume=393|issue=10172|pages=655\u2013663|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(18)32531-5|pmid=30782341|pmc=6381229}}</ref>\n\n==Medical uses==\n{{multiple image\n   | direction = horizontal\n   | footer    = X-ray of total knee replacement, anteroposterior view (left) and lateral view (right)\n   | image1    = Postoperative X-ray of normal knee prosthesis, anteroposterior view.jpg\n   | alt1      = \n   | caption1  = \n   | width1     = 150\n   | image2    = Postoperative X-ray of normal knee prosthesis, lateral view.jpg\n   | alt2      =\n   | caption2  = \n   | width2     = 170}}\n[[Image:Knee Replacement.jpg|thumb|The incision for knee replacement surgery]]\n\nKnee replacement surgery is most commonly performed in people with advanced [[osteoarthritis]] and should be considered when conservative treatments have been exhausted.<ref name=\"Management\">{{cite journal|last1=Van Manen|first1=MD|last2=Nace|first2=J|last3=Mont|first3=MA|title=Management of primary knee osteoarthritis and indications for total knee arthroplasty for general practitioners.|journal=The Journal of the American Osteopathic Association|volume=112 |issue=11 |pages=709\u2013715 |date=November 2012 |pmid=23139341}}</ref> Total knee replacement is also an option to correct significant knee joint or bone trauma in young patients.  Similarly, total knee replacement can be performed to correct mild [[valgus deformity|valgus]] or [[varus deformity]]. Serious valgus or varus deformity should be corrected by [[osteotomy]]. [[Physical therapy]] has been shown to improve function and may delay or prevent the need for knee replacement. Pain is often noted when performing physical activities requiring a wide range of motion in the knee joint.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Deyle GD, Henderson NE, Matekel RL, Ryder MG, Garber MB, Allison SC |title=Effectiveness of manual physical therapy and exercise in osteoarthritis of the knee. A randomized, controlled trial |journal=Ann. Intern. Med. |volume=132 |issue=3 |pages=173\u201381 |date=February 2000 |pmid=10651597 |url=http://www.annals.org/article.aspx?volume=132&page=173 |doi=10.7326/0003-4819-132-3-200002010-00002}}</ref>\n\n==Pre-operative preparation==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" width=\"180px\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| [[File:HKA and HKS angles.jpg|70px]]\n| Angles commonly measured before knee replacement surgery:\n*Hip-knee-shaft angle (HKS)<ref name=cooke2007>{{cite journal|vauthors=Cooke TD, Sled EA, Scudamore RA | title=Frontal plane knee alignment: a call for standardized measurement. | journal=J Rheumatol | year= 2007 | volume= 34 | issue= 9 | pages= 1796\u2013801 | pmid=17787049 | doi= | pmc= }}</ref>\n*Hip-knee-ankle angle (HKA)<ref name=dahl2009>{{cite journal|last1=W-Dahl|first1=Annette|last2=Toksvig-Larsen|first2=S\u00f6ren|last3=Roos|first3=Ewa M|title=Association between knee alignment and knee pain in patients surgically treated for medial knee osteoarthritis by high tibial osteotomy. A one year follow-up study|journal=BMC Musculoskeletal Disorders|volume=10|issue=1|pages=154|year=2009|issn=1471-2474|doi=10.1186/1471-2474-10-154|pmid=19995425|pmc=2796991}}</ref>\n|}\n\nTo indicate knee replacement in case of [[osteoarthritis]], its [[radiographic classification of osteoarthritis|radiographic classification]] and severity of symptoms should both be substantial. Such radiography should consist of weightbearing [[projectional radiography|X-rays]] of both knees- AP, Lateral, and 30 degrees of flexion. AP and lateral views may not show joint space narrowing, but the 30 degree flexion view is most sensitive for narrowing. Full length projections are also used in order to adjust the prosthesis to provide a neutral angle for the distal lower extremity. Two angles used for this purpose are:\n*Hip-knee-shaft angle (HKS),<ref name=cooke2007/> an angle formed between a line through the longitudinal axis of the [[femur|femoral]] shaft and its mechanical axis, which is a line from the center of the [[femoral head]] to the intercondylar notch of the distal femur.<ref name=\"CherianKapadia2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Cherian|first1=Jeffrey J.|last2=Kapadia|first2=Bhaveen H.|last3=Banerjee|first3=Samik|last4=Jauregui|first4=Julio J.|last5=Issa|first5=Kimona|last6=Mont|first6=Michael A.|title=Mechanical, Anatomical, and Kinematic Axis in TKA: Concepts and Practical Applications|journal=Current Reviews in Musculoskeletal Medicine|volume=7|issue=2|year=2014|pages=89\u201395|issn=1935-973X|doi=10.1007/s12178-014-9218-y|pmid=24671469|pmc=4092202}}</ref>\n*Hip-knee-ankle angle (HKA),<ref name=\"dahl2009\"/> which is an angle between the femoral mechanical axis and the center of the [[ankle joint]].<ref name=\"CherianKapadia2014\"/> It is normally between 1.0\u00b0 and 1.5\u00b0 of varus in adults.<ref name=\"SheehyFelson2011\">{{cite journal|last1=Sheehy|first1=L.|last2=Felson|first2=D.|last3=Zhang|first3=Y.|last4=Niu|first4=J.|last5=Lam|first5=Y.-M.|last6=Segal|first6=N.|last7=Lynch|first7=J.|last8=Cooke|first8=T.D.V.|title=Does measurement of the anatomic axis consistently predict hip-knee-ankle angle (HKA) for knee alignment studies in osteoarthritis? Analysis of long limb radiographs from the multicenter osteoarthritis (MOST) study|journal=Osteoarthritis and Cartilage|volume=19|issue=1|year=2011|pages=58\u201364|issn=10634584|doi=10.1016/j.joca.2010.09.011|pmid=20950695|pmc=3038654}}</ref>\n\nThe patient is to perform range of motion exercises and hip, knee and ankle strengthening as directed daily.  Before the surgery is performed, pre-operative tests are done: usually a [[complete blood count]], [[electrolytes]], [[APTT]] and [[Prothrombin time|PT]] to measure [[coagulation|blood clotting]], [[chest X-ray]]s, [[ECG]], and blood [[cross-matching]] for possible [[blood transfusion|transfusion]]. About a month before the surgery, the patient may be prescribed supplemental iron to boost the hemoglobin in their blood system. Accurate X-rays of the affected knee are needed to measure the size of components which will be needed. Medications such as [[warfarin]] and [[aspirin]] will be stopped some days before surgery to reduce the amount of bleeding. Patients may be admitted on the day of surgery if the pre-op work-up is done in the pre-[[anesthetic]] clinic or may come into [[hospital]] one or more days before surgery.  Currently there is insufficient quality evidence to support the use of pre-operative physiotherapy in older adults undergoing total knee arthroplasty.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chesham|first1=Ross Alexander|last2=Shanmugam|first2=Sivaramkumar|title=Does preoperative physiotherapy improve postoperative, patient-based outcomes in older adults who have undergone total knee arthroplasty? A systematic review|journal=Physiotherapy Theory and Practice|volume=33|issue=1|date=13 October 2016|pages=9\u201330|doi=10.1080/09593985.2016.1230660|pmid=27736286}}</ref>\n\nPreoperative education is currently an important part of patient care. There is some evidence that it may slightly reduce anxiety before knee replacement surgery, with low risk of detrimental effects.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McDonald|first=S|last2=Page|first2=MJ|last3=Beringer|first3=K|last4=Wasiak|first4=J|last5=Sprowson|first5=A|date=13 May 2014|title=Preoperative education for hip or knee replacement|url=|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=|issue=5|pages=CD003526|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD003526.pub3|pmid=24820247}}</ref>\n\n[[Bariatric surgery|Weight loss surgery]] before a knee replacement does not appear to change outcomes.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Smith|first1=TO|last2=Aboelmagd|first2=T|last3=Hing|first3=CB|last4=MacGregor|first4=A|title=Does bariatric surgery prior to total hip or knee arthroplasty reduce post-operative complications and improve clinical outcomes for obese patients? Systematic review and meta-analysis.|journal=The Bone & Joint Journal|date=September 2016|volume=98-B|issue=9|pages=1160\u20136|pmid=27587514|doi=10.1302/0301-620x.98b9.38024|url=https://ueaeprints.uea.ac.uk/58880/1/Bariatric_surgery_paper_ACCEPTED_10.05.2016.pdf}}<!--https://ueaeprints.uea.ac.uk/58880/1/Bariatric_surgery_paper_ACCEPTED_10.05.2016.pdf--></ref>\n\n==Technique==\n[[Image:Prothese-genou-IMG 0033.jpg|150px|thumb|left|Model of total knee replacement]]\nThe [[surgery]] involves exposure of the front of the knee, with detachment of part of the [[quadriceps muscle]] ([[vastus medialis]]) from the [[patella]].  The [[patella]] is displaced to one side of the joint, allowing exposure of the [[Anatomical terms of location|distal]] end of the [[femur]] and the [[Anatomical terms of location|proximal]] end of the [[tibia]]. The ends of these bones are then accurately cut to shape using cutting guides oriented to the long axis of the bones. The [[cartilage]]s and the [[anterior cruciate ligament]] are removed; the [[posterior cruciate ligament]] may also be removed but the [[medial collateral ligament|tibial]] and [[fibular collateral ligament|fibular]] collateral ligaments are preserved.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Verra|first=Wiebe C.|last2=van den Boom|first2=Lennard G. H.|last3=Jacobs|first3=Wilco|last4=Clement|first4=Darren J.|last5=Wymenga|first5=Ate A. B.|last6=Nelissen|first6=Rob G. H. H.|date=2013-10-11|title=Retention versus sacrifice of the posterior cruciate ligament in total knee arthroplasty for treating osteoarthritis|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|issue=10|pages=CD004803|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD004803.pub3|issn=1469-493X|pmc=6599815|pmid=24114343}}</ref> Whether the posterior cruciate ligament is removed or preserved depends on the type of implant used, although there appears to be no clear difference in knee function or range of motion favouring either approach.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Verra |first1=WC |last2=van den Boom |first2=LG |last3=Jacobs |first3=W |last4=Clement |first4=DJ |last5=Wymenga |first5=AA |last6=Nelissen |first6=RG |title=Retention versus sacrifice of the posterior cruciate ligament in total knee arthroplasty for treating osteoarthritis. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=11 October 2013 |issue=10 |pages=CD004803 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD004803.pub3 |pmid=24114343|pmc=6599815 }}</ref> Metal components are then impacted onto the bone or fixed using [[polymethylmethacrylate]] (PMMA) cement. Alternative techniques exist that affix the implant without cement.  These cement-less techniques may involve [[osseointegration]], including [[metal foam|porous metal]] prostheses. Finally, stability and range of motion is checked, followed by [[Therapeutic irrigation|irrigation]], [[hemostasis]], placement of hemovacs, and closure.<ref> [https://jomi.com/article/20/posterior-cruciate-retaining-total-knee-arthroplasty/] Scott MD R. Posterior cruciate-retaining total knee arthroplasty. J Med Ins. 2017;2017(20). doi:https://doi.org/10.24296/jomi/20</ref>\n\n===Femoral replacement===\nA round ended implant is used for the femur, mimicking the natural shape of the joint. On the tibia the component is flat, although it sometimes has a stem which goes down inside the bone for further stability. A flattened or slightly dished [[high-density polyethylene]] surface is then inserted onto the tibial component so that the weight is transferred metal to plastic not metal to metal. During the operation any deformities must be corrected, and the ligaments balanced so that the knee has a good range of movement and is stable and aligned. In some cases the articular surface of the patella is also removed and replaced by a polyethylene button cemented to the posterior surface of the patella.  In other cases, the patella is replaced unaltered.\n\n===Post-operative pain control===\nThe regional analgesia techniques (neuraxial anesthesia or continuous femoral nerve block<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Toftdahl|first1=K|last2=Nikolajsen|first2=L|last3=Haraldsted|first3=V|last4=Madsen|first4=F|last5=T\u00f8nnesen|first5=EK|last6=S\u00f8balle|first6=K|title=Comparison of peri- and intraarticular analgesia with femoral nerve block after total knee arthroplasty: a randomized clinical trial.|journal=Acta Orthopaedica|date=April 2007|volume=78|issue=2|pages=172\u20139|doi=10.1080/17453670710013645|pmid=17464603}}</ref> or adductor canal block) are used most commonly.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Practice guidelines for acute pain management in the perioperative setting: an updated report by the American Society of Anesthesiologists Task Force on Acute Pain Management|journal=Anesthesiology|volume=116|issue=2|pages=248\u2013273|doi=10.1097/ALN.0b013e31823c1030|pmid=22227789|date=February 2012|author1=American Society of Anesthesiologists Task Force on Acute Pain Management}}</ref> Local anesthesia infiltration in the pericapsular area using liposomal bupivacaine provides good analgesia in the post-operative period without increasing the risk for instability or nerve injury.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Essving|first1=P|last2=Axelsson|first2=K|last3=\u00c5berg|first3=E|last4=Sp\u00e4nnar|first4=H|last5=Gupta|first5=A|last6=Lundin|first6=A|title=Local infiltration analgesia versus intrathecal morphine for postoperative pain management after total knee arthroplasty: a randomized controlled trial.|journal=Anesthesia & Analgesia|date=October 2011|volume=113|issue=4|pages=926\u201333|doi=10.1213/ANE.0b013e3182288deb|pmid=21821506|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/eba9ed5e95c44f4ede12fc3890cbdd096a5cec69}}</ref> A combined approach of local infiltration analgesia and femoral nerve block to achieve multimodal analgesia is common.\n\n==Variations==\n{{medref|section|date=July 2019}}\n\nVariations in manufacture and surgical preparation for knee replacement occur between cemented and uncemented components, between resurfacing the patella or not, and between denervating the patella using electrocautery or not. Cemented-fixation may be more vulnerable to future aseptic loosening than the cement-less technique.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nakama|first=Gilberto Yoshinobu|last2=Peccin|first2=Maria Stella|last3=Almeida|first3=Gustavo JM|last4=Lira Neto|first4=Oz\u00f3rio de Almeida|last5=Queiroz|first5=Ant\u00f4nio AB|last6=Navarro|first6=Ricardo Dizioli|date=2012-10-17|title=Cemented, cementless or hybrid fixation options in total knee arthroplasty for osteoarthritis and other non-traumatic diseases|journal=Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=10|pages=CD006193|doi=10.1002/14651858.cd006193.pub2|pmid=23076921|issn=1465-1858}}</ref>\n\nRetaining the posterior cruciate ligament (PCL) has been shown to be beneficial for patients. Removal of the PCL has been shown to reduce the maximal force that the individual can place on that knee.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Mahoney OM, Noble PC, Rhoads DD, Alexander JW, Tullos HS |title=Posterior cruciate function following total knee arthroplasty. A biomechanical study |journal=J Arthroplasty |volume=9 |issue=6 |pages=569\u201378 |date=December 1994 |pmid=7699369 |doi=10.1016/0883-5403(94)90110-4}}</ref> Typically individuals who have the PCL removed will lean forward while climbing in order to maximize the force of the quadriceps. A variation in the total knee replacement procedure is to permit movement in the prostheses using a polyethylene insert, an approach called a mobile bearing total knee arthroplasty.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Hofstede|first=Stefanie N.|last2=Nouta|first2=Klaas Auke|last3=Jacobs|first3=Wilco|last4=van Hooff|first4=Miranda L.|last5=Wymenga|first5=Ate B.|last6=Pijls|first6=Bart G.|last7=Nelissen|first7=Rob G. H. H.|last8=Marang-van de Mheen|first8=Perla J.|date=2015|title=Mobile bearing vs fixed bearing prostheses for posterior cruciate retaining total knee arthroplasty for postoperative functional status in patients with osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis|url=|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=|issue=2|pages=CD003130|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD003130.pub3|issn=1469-493X|pmid=25650566}}</ref> There is no strong evidence that this approach improves knee function, mortality, number of adverse effects, or amount of pain compared to a fixed bearing approach for total knee replacement that retains the PCL.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n[[Minimally invasive procedure]]s have been developed in total knee replacement that do not cut the [[quadriceps tendon]]. There are different definitions of minimally invasive knee surgery, which may include a shorter incision length, retraction of the patella without eversion (rotating out), and specialized instruments. There are few randomized trials, but studies have found less postoperative pain, shorter hospital stays, and shorter recovery. However, no studies have shown long-term benefits.<ref name=Leopold09/>\n\n=== Partial knee replacement ===\n{{Main|Unicompartmental knee arthroplasty}}\nUnicompartmental arthroplasty (UKA), also called [[partial knee replacement]], is an option for some people. The knee is generally divided into three \"compartments\": ''medial'', ''lateral'', and ''patellofemoral''. Most people with arthritis severe enough to consider knee replacement have significant wear in two or more of the above compartments, and are treated with total knee replacement (TKA). A minority of people with osteoarthritis have wear primarily in one compartment, usually the medial, and may be candidates for unicompartmental knee replacement. Advantages of UKA compared to TKA include smaller incision, easier post-op rehabilitation, better postoperative range of motion, shorter hospital stay, less blood loss, lower risk of infection, stiffness, and [[blood clot]]s, but a harder revision if necessary. Persons with infectious or inflammatory arthritis ([[rheumatoid arthritis]], [[lupus erythematosus|lupus]], [[psoriasis]]), or marked deformity are not candidates for this procedure.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=U4u9BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA203&lpg=PA203&dq=partial+knee+replacement+Persons+with+infectious+or+inflammatory+arthritis+(rheumatoid+arthritis,+lupus,+psoriasis),+or+marked+deformity+are+not+candidates+for+this+procedure#v=onepage&q=partial%20knee%20replacement%20Persons%20with%20infectious%20or%20inflammatory%20arthritis%20(rheumatoid%20arthritis,%20lupus,%20psoriasis),%20or%20marked%20deformity%20are%20not%20candidates%20for%20this%20procedure&f=false|title=Design of Artificial Human Joints & Organs|last=Pal|first=Subrata|date=2013-08-31|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-1-4614-6255-2|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Components and zones==\n{{anchor|KS zones}}[[File:Knee prosthesis zones by Knee Society 2015, lateral view.jpg|thumb|150px|KS (Knee Society) zones, lateral view.<ref name=\"MeneghiniMont2015\">{{cite journal|last1=Meneghini|first1=R. Michael|last2=Mont|first2=Michael A.|last3=Backstein|first3=David B.|last4=Bourne|first4=Robert B.|last5=Dennis|first5=Doug A.|last6=Scuderi|first6=Giles R.|title=Development of a Modern Knee Society Radiographic Evaluation System and Methodology for Total Knee Arthroplasty|journal=The Journal of Arthroplasty|volume=30|issue=12|year=2015|pages=2311\u20132314|issn=08835403|doi=10.1016/j.arth.2015.05.049|pmid=26122112}}</ref>]]\n\nStandardized zones around the components are used for specifying for example signs of loosening on radiographic follow-up. There are various classification systems for specifying such zones,<ref name=\"NapierO\u2019Neill2018\">{{cite journal|last1=Napier|first1=Richard J.|last2=O\u2019Neill|first2=Christopher|last3=O\u2019Brien|first3=Seamus|last4=Doran|first4=Emer|last5=Mockford|first5=Brian|last6=Boldt|first6=Jens|last7=Beverland|first7=David E.|title=A prospective evaluation of a largely cementless total knee arthroplasty cohort without patellar resurfacing: 10-year outcomes and survivorship|journal=BMC Musculoskeletal Disorders|volume=19|issue=1|pages=205|year=2018|issn=1471-2474|doi=10.1186/s12891-018-2128-1|pmid=29945574|pmc=6020353}}</ref><ref name=\"KumarYadav2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Kumar|first1=Nishikant|last2=Yadav|first2=Chandrashekhar|last3=Raj|first3=Rishi|last4=Anand|first4=Sumit|title=How to Interpret Postoperative X-rays after Total Knee Arthroplasty|journal=Orthopaedic Surgery|volume=6|issue=3|year=2014|pages=179\u2013186|issn=17577853|doi=10.1111/os.12123|pmid=25179351|pmc=6583264}}</ref> including by KS (Knee Society) zones published in 2015.<ref name=\"MeneghiniMont2015\"/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"140\">\nFile:Knee prosthesis components.jpg|Main components of a knee prosthesis.\nFile:Knee prosthesis zones by Knee Society 2015, AP view.jpg|KS zones, anteroposterior (AP) view.<ref name=\"MeneghiniMont2015\"/>\n</gallery>\n\nSpecific KS zones are as follows, with * meaning that the zone can be specified as \"A\" (anterior), \"P\" (posterior), \"M\" (medial) or \"L\" (lateral):<ref name=\"MeneghiniMont2015\"/>\n*Femoral component (lateral view)\n:*Zone 1 and 2: Anterior and posterior flange, respectively.\n:*Zone 3: Central box/distal fixation region, where \"A\" and \"P\" designate the respective chamfers if visible*\n:*Zone 4: Stem extension*\n:*Zone 5: Stem\n*Tibial component:\n:*Zone 1: Anterior on lateral view, medial on anteroposterior (AP) view.\n:*Zone 2: Posterior on lateral view, lateral on AP view.\n:*Zone 3: Central keel/stem/peg fixation region*\n:*Zone 4: Stem extension*\n:*Zone 5: Inferior aspect of keel or stem\n\n==Risks==\n\nRisks and complications in knee replacement<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.vims.ac.in/healthcare/joint-replace-recovery-process.html | title=Knee Replacement Surgery in Bangalore - Vydehi Hopsital}}</ref> are similar to those associated with all [[Joint replacement#Risks and complications|joint replacements]]. The most serious complication is infection of the joint, which occurs in <1% of patients. Risk factors for infection are related to both patient and surgical factors.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tayton|first=E. R.|last2=Frampton|first2=C.|last3=Hooper|first3=G. J.|last4=Young|first4=S. W.|date=1 March 2016|title=The impact of patient and surgical factors on the rate of infection after primary total knee arthroplasty|journal=Bone Joint J|language=en|volume=98-B|issue=3|pages=334\u2013340|doi=10.1302/0301-620X.98B3.36775|issn=2049-4394|pmid=26920958|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/29599c765c5af3554b8517df19fb81f426261e88}}</ref> [[Deep vein thrombosis]] occurs in up to 15% of patients, and is symptomatic in 2\u20133%. Nerve injuries occur in 1\u20132% of patients. Persistent pain or stiffness occurs in 8\u201323% of patients. Prosthesis failure occurs in approximately 2% of patients at 5 years.<ref name=Leopold09/>\n\nThere is increased risk of complications for [[obese]] people going through total knee replacement.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kerkhoffs|first=GM|author2=Servien, E |author3=Dunn, W |author4=Dahm, D |author5=Bramer, JA |author6= Haverkamp, D |title=The influence of obesity on the complication rate and outcome of total knee arthroplasty: a meta-analysis and systematic literature review.|journal=The Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery. American Volume|date=17 October 2012|volume=94|issue=20|pages=1839\u201344|pmid=23079875|doi=10.2106/JBJS.K.00820|pmc=3489068}}</ref> The morbidly obese should be advised to lose weight before surgery and, if medically eligible, would probably benefit from [[bariatric surgery]].<ref>\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Samson AJ, Mercer GE, Campbell DG |title=Total knee replacement in the morbidly obese: a literature review |journal=ANZ J Surg |volume=80 |issue=9 |pages=595\u20139 |date=September 2010 |pmid=20840400 |doi=10.1111/j.1445-2197.2010.05396.x }}</ref>\n\nFracturing or chipping of the polyethylene platform between the femoral and tibial components may be of concern. These fragments may become lodged in the knee and create pain or may move to other parts of the body. Advancements in implant design have greatly reduced these issues but the potential for concern is still present over the lifespan of the knee replacement.\n\n===Deep vein thrombosis===\nAccording to the American Academy of Orthopedic Surgeons (AAOS), [[deep vein thrombosis]] in the leg is \"the most common complication of knee replacement surgery... prevention... may include periodic elevation of patient's legs, lower leg exercises to increase circulation, support stockings and medication to thin your blood.\"<ref name=\"AAOS\"/>\n\n===Fractures===\n[[Periprosthetic]] fractures are becoming more frequent with the aging patient population and can occur intraoperatively or postoperatively. Depending on the location of the fracture and the stability of the prosthesis, these can be treated surgically with open reduction and internal fixation or revision of the prosthesis.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n===Loss of motion===\nThe knee at times may not recover its normal range of motion (0\u2013135 degrees usually) after total knee replacement. Much of this is dependent on pre-operative function. Most patients can achieve 0\u2013110 degrees, but stiffness of the joint can occur. In some situations, manipulation of the knee under anesthetic is used to reduce post operative stiffness. There are also many implants from manufacturers that are designed to be \"high-flex\" knees, offering a greater range of motion.\n\n===Instability===\nIn some patients, the kneecap dislocates to the outer side of the knee after surgery. This is painful and usually needs to be treated by surgery to realign the kneecap. However, this is quite rare.\n\n===Loosening===\nLoosening of the prosthesis can be indicated on [[Projectional radiography|X-ray]] by thin radiolucenct spaces around the implant, or more obviously by implant displacement.<ref name=\"Cyteval2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Cyteval|first1=C.|title=Imaging of knee implants and related complications|journal=Diagnostic and Interventional Imaging|volume=97|issue=7\u20138|year=2016|pages=809\u2013821|issn=22115684|doi=10.1016/j.diii.2016.02.015|pmid=27423710}}</ref> \n\n===Infection===\nThe current classification of AAOS divides prosthetic infections into four types.<ref name=\"pmid16958480\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Leone JM, Hanssen AD |title=Management of infection at the site of a total knee arthroplasty |journal=Instr Course Lect |volume=55 |pages=449\u201361 |year=2006 |pmid=16958480 |doi=}}</ref>\n* Type 1 (positive intraoperative culture): Two positive intraoperative cultures\n* Type 2 (early postoperative infection): Infection occurring within first month after surgery\n* Type 3 (acute hematogenous infection): Hematogenous seeding of site of previously well-functioning prosthesis\n* Type 4 (late chronic infection): Chronic indolent clinical course; infection present for more than a month\n\nWhile it is relatively rare, periprosthetic infection remains one of the most challenging complications of joint arthroplasty.\nA detailed clinical history and physical remain the most reliable tool to recognize a potential periprosthetic infection. In some cases the classic signs of fever, chills, painful joint, and a draining sinus may be present, and diagnostic studies are simply done to confirm the diagnosis. In reality though, most patients do not present with those clinical signs, and in fact the clinical presentation may overlap with other complications such as aseptic loosening and pain. In those cases diagnostic tests can be useful in confirming or excluding infection.\n\n[[File:ProthesenlockerungPET-CT.jpg|thumb|FDG-PET CT showing septic loosening of knee prothesis; the FDG-enrichment shows entensive inflammatory foci: demonstrative: the PET-image ist unlike the CT reconstruction not disturbed by the high radiation attenuation of the prothesis.]]\n\nModern diagnosis of infection around a total knee replacement is based on the Musculoskeletal Infection Society (MSIS) criteria.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Parvizi|first1=Javad|last2=Zmistowski|first2=Benjamin|last3=Berbari|first3=Elie F.|last4=Bauer|first4=Thomas W.|last5=Springer|first5=Bryan D.|last6=Della Valle|first6=Craig J.|last7=Garvin|first7=Kevin L.|last8=Mont|first8=Michael A.|last9=Wongworawat|first9=Montri D.|last10=Zalavras|first10=Charalampos G.|title=New Definition for Periprosthetic Joint Infection: From the Workgroup of the Musculoskeletal Infection Society|journal=Clinical Orthopaedics and Related Research|date=22 September 2011|volume=469|issue=11|pages=2992\u20132994|doi=10.1007/s11999-011-2102-9|pmid=21938532|pmc=3183178}}</ref> They are:\n\n1. There is a sinus tract communicating with the prosthesis; or\n2. A pathogen is isolated by culture from at least two separate tissue or fluid samples obtained from the affected prosthetic joint; \nor\n\nFour of the following six criteria exist:\n\n1.Elevated serum erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR>30mm/hr) and serum C-reactive protein (CRP>10&nbsp;mg/L) concentration,\n\n2.Elevated synovial leukocyte count,\n\n3.Elevated synovial neutrophil percentage (PMN%),\n\n4.Presence of purulence in the affected joint,\n\n5.Isolation of a microorganism in one culture of periprosthetic tissue or fluid, or\n\n6. Greater than five neutrophils per high-power field in five high-power fields observed from histologic analysis of periprosthetic tissue at \u00d7400 magnification.\n\nNone of the above laboratory tests has 100% sensitivity or specificity for diagnosing infection. Specificity improves when the tests are performed in patients in whom clinical suspicion exists. ESR and CRP remain good 1st line tests for screening (high sensitivity, low specificity).  Aspiration of the joint remains the test with the highest specificity for confirming infection.\n\nThe choice of treatment depends on the type of prosthetic infection.<ref name=\"pmid10535593\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Segawa H, Tsukayama DT, Kyle RF, Becker DA, Gustilo RB |title=Infection after total knee arthroplasty. A retrospective study of the treatment of eighty-one infections |journal=J Bone Joint Surg Am |volume=81 |issue=10 |pages=1434\u201345 |year=1999 |pmid=10535593 |doi=10.2106/00004623-199910000-00008}}</ref>\n\n#Positive intraoperative cultures: Antibiotic therapy alone\n#Early post-operative infections: debridement, antibiotics, and retention of prosthesis.\n#Acute hematogenous infections: debridement, antibiotic therapy, retention of prosthesis.\n#Late chronic: delayed exchange arthroplasty. Surgical d\u00e9bridement and parenteral antibiotics alone in this group has limited success, and standard of care involves exchange arthroplasty.<ref name=\"pmid17438469\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Chiu FY, Chen CM |title=Surgical d\u00e9bridement and parenteral antibiotics in infected revision total knee arthroplasty |journal=Clin. Orthop. Relat. Res. |volume=461 |pages=130\u20135 |year=2007 |pmid=17438469 |doi=10.1097/BLO.0b013e318063e7f3}}</ref>\n\nAppropriate antibiotic doses can be found at the following instructional course lecture by AAOS<ref name=\"pmid16958480\"/>\n\n==Post-operative evaluation==\n[[File:X-ray of knee prosthesis with overhang, annotated.jpg|thumb|150px|Overhang (arrow) does not seem to have any detrimental effect.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Impact Of Tibial Component Overhang On Outcome Scores And Pain In Total Knee Replacement|date=2018-02-21|author=S.G.F. Abram, A.G Marsh, F. Nicol, A.S. Brydone, A. Mohammed, S.J. Spencer|journal=Orthopaedic Proceedings}}</ref>]]\nKnee replacement is routinely evaluated by [[Projectional radiograph|X-ray]], including the following measures:\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"380\">\nFile:X-ray of HKA angle with knee prosthesis.jpg|'''HKA''': Hip-knee-ankle angle, which is ideally between 3\u00b0 [[genu varum|varum]] to 3\u00b0 [[Genu valgum|valgum]] from a [[right angle]].<ref name=Inui2013>{{cite journal|last1=Inui|first1=Hiroshi|last2=Taketomi|first2=Shuji|last3=Nakamura|first3=Kensuke|last4=Takei|first4=Seira|last5=Takeda|first5=Hideki|last6=Tanaka|first6=Sakae|last7=Nakagawa|first7=Takumi|title=Influence of navigation system updates on total knee arthroplasty|journal=Sports Medicine, Arthroscopy, Rehabilitation, Therapy & Technology|volume=5|issue=1|pages=10|year=2013|issn=1758-2555|doi=10.1186/2052-1847-5-10|pmid=23638774|pmc=3653716}} [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0 (CC-BY-2.0)]</ref>\nFile:Postoperative X-ray of normal knee prosthesis, anteroposterior view, annotated.jpg|- '''FFC''': frontal femoral component angle. It is typically regarded as optimal when being 2\u20137\u00b0 in valgus.<ref name=\"GromovKorchi2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Gromov|first1=Kirill|last2=Korchi|first2=Mounim|last3=Thomsen|first3=Morten G|last4=Husted|first4=Henrik|last5=Troelsen|first5=Anders|title=What is the optimal alignment of the tibial and femoral components in knee arthroplasty?|journal=Acta Orthopaedica|volume=85|issue=5|year=2014|pages=480\u2013487|issn=1745-3674|doi=10.3109/17453674.2014.940573|pmid=25036719|pmc=4164865}}</ref><br>- '''FTC''': frontal tibial component angle, which is regarded as optimal when being at a [[right angle]]. A varus position of more than 3\u00b0 has generally been found to increase the failure rate of the prosthesis.<ref name=\"GromovKorchi2014\"/>\nFile:Postoperative X-ray of normal knee prosthesis, lateral view, annotated.jpg|- '''Anterior femoral notching''' (the femoral component causing reduced thickness of the distal femur anteriorly), seems to cause an increased risk of fractures when exceeding about 3 mm.<ref name=\"LeeWang2015\">{{cite journal|last1=Lee|first1=Ju Hong|last2=Wang|first2=Seong-Il|title=Risk of Anterior Femoral Notching in Navigated Total Knee Arthroplasty|journal=Clinics in Orthopedic Surgery|volume=7|issue=2|year=2015|pages=217\u201324|issn=2005-291X|doi=10.4055/cios.2015.7.2.217|pmid=26217469|pmc=4515463}}</ref><br>- '''LTC''': lateral (or sagittal) tibial component angle, which is ideally positioned so that the tibia is 0\u20137\u00b0 flexed compared to at a right angle with the tibial plate.<ref name=\"GromovKorchi2014\"/>\n</gallery>\n\n==Post-operative rehabilitation==\nThe length of post-operative hospitalization is 5 days on average depending on the health status of the patient and the amount of support available outside the hospital setting.<ref name=\"CarterPotts2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Carter|first1=Evelene M|last2=Potts|first2=Henry WW|title=Predicting length of stay from an electronic patient record system: a primary total knee replacement example|journal=BMC Medical Informatics and Decision Making|volume=14|issue=1|year=2014|pages=26|issn=1472-6947|doi=10.1186/1472-6947-14-26|pmid=24708853|pmc=3992140}}</ref> Protected [[weight bearing]] on crutches or a [[Walker (tool)|walker]] is required until specified by the surgeon<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.massgeneral.org/ortho-hip-knee/patient-education/pt-ed-kneerehab.pdf|title=Rehabilitation|last=|first=|date=|website=massgeneral.org|access-date=}}</ref> because of weakness in the quadriceps muscle<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Valtonen|first=Anu|last2=P\u00f6yh\u00f6nen|first2=Tapani|last3=Heinonen|first3=Ari|last4=Sipil\u00e4|first4=Sarianna|date=1 October 2009|title=Muscle Deficits Persist After Unilateral Knee Replacement and Have Implications for Rehabilitation|journal=Physical Therapy|language=en|volume=89|issue=10|pages=1072\u20131079|doi=10.2522/ptj.20070295|issn=0031-9023|pmid=19713269|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the immediate post-operative period, up to 39% of knee replacement patients experience inadequate pain control.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Michael M. H.|last2=Hartley|first2=Rebecca L.|last3=Leung|first3=Alexander A.|last4=Ronksley|first4=Paul E.|last5=Jett\u00e9|first5=Nathalie|last6=Casha|first6=Steven|last7=Riva-Cambrin|first7=Jay|date=2019-04-01|title=Preoperative predictors of poor acute postoperative pain control: a systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=BMJ Open|volume=9|issue=4|pages=e025091|doi=10.1136/bmjopen-2018-025091|issn=2044-6055|pmid=30940757|pmc=6500309}}</ref>\n\nTo increase the likelihood of a good outcome after surgery, multiple weeks of [[physical therapy]] is necessary. In these weeks, the therapist will help the patient return to normal activities, as well as prevent blood clots, improve circulation, increase range of motion, and eventually strengthen the surrounding muscles through specific exercises. Whether techniques such as [[neuromuscular electrical stimulation]] are effective at promoting gains in knee muscle strength after surgery are unclear.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Monaghan |first1=B |last2=Caulfield |first2=B |last3=O'Math\u00fana |first3=DP |title=Surface neuromuscular electrical stimulation for quadriceps strengthening pre and post total knee replacement. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=20 January 2010 |issue=1 |pages=CD007177 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD007177.pub2 |pmid=20091621|url=http://doras.dcu.ie/19651/1/dpom4.pdf }}</ref>\nOften range of motion (to the limits of the prosthesis) is recovered over the first two weeks (the earlier the better). Over time, patients are able to increase the amount of weight bearing on the operated leg, and eventually are able to tolerate full weight bearing with the guidance of the physical therapist.<ref name=\":0\" /> After about ten months, the patient should be able to return to normal daily activities, although the operated leg may be significantly weaker than the non-operated leg.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFor post-operative knee replacement patients, immobility is a factor precipitated by pain and other complications. Mobility is known as an important aspect of human biology that has many beneficial effects on the body system.<ref>Leah, 2013 {{full citation needed|date=April 2018}}</ref> It is well documented in literature that physical immobility affects every body system and contributes to functional complications of prolonged illness.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1097/cnq.0b013e3182750631| pmid = 23221435| title = Foreword| journal = Critical Care Nursing Quarterly| volume = 36| issue = 1| pages = 1\u20132| year = 2013| last1 = &Na| last2 = Dickinson| first2 = S}}</ref> In most medical-surgical hospital units that perform knee replacements, ambulation is a key aspect of nursing care that is promoted to patients. Early ambulation can decrease the risk of complications associated with immobilization such as pressure ulcers, deep vein thrombosis (DVT), impaired pulmonary function, and loss of functional mobility.<ref name=\"Teodoro, 2016\">Teodoro, 2016 {{full citation needed|date=April 2018}}</ref> Nurses\u2019 promotion and execution of early ambulation on patients has found that it greatly reduces the complications listed above, as well as decreases length of stay and costs associated with further hospitalization.<ref name=\"Teodoro, 2016\"/> Nurses may also work with teams such as physical therapy and occupational therapy to accomplish ambulation goals and reduce complications.<ref>Ong & Pua, 2011{{full citation needed|date=April 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Continuous passive motion]] (CPM) is a postoperative therapy approach that uses a machine to move the knee continuously through a specific range of motion, with the goal of preventing joint stiffness and improving recovery.<ref name=\"APTAfive\">{{Citation|title=Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question|date=15 September 2014|url=http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-physical-therapy-association/|author1=American Physical Therapy Association|author1-link=American Physical Therapy Association|work=[[Choosing Wisely]]: an initiative of the [[ABIM Foundation]]|page=|publisher=American Physical Therapy Association|accessdate=15 September 2014}} \n</ref><ref name=Harvey2014>{{Cite journal|last=Harvey|first=Lisa A.|last2=Brosseau|first2=Lucie|last3=Herbert|first3=Robert D.|date=2014-02-06|title=Continuous passive motion following total knee arthroplasty in people with arthritis|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/6c7a31933b39657ebe61c95a9ab4a4383aff5a13|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=|issue=2|pages=CD004260|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD004260.pub3|issn=1469-493X|pmid=24500904}}</ref> There is no evidence that CPM therapy leads to a clinically significant improvement in range of motion, pain, knee function, or quality of life.<ref name=Harvey2014 /> CPM is inexpensive, convenient, and assists patients in therapeutic compliance. However, CPM should be used in conjunction with traditional physical therapy.<ref name=\"APTAfive\"/> In unusual cases where the person has a problem which prevents standard mobilization treatment, then CPM may be useful.<ref name=\"APTAfive\"/>\n\n[[Cryotherapy]], also known as 'cold therapy' is sometimes recommended after surgery for pain relief and to limit swelling of the knee. Cryotherapy involves the application of ice bags or cooled water to the skin of the knee joint. However, the evidence that cryotherapy reduces pain and swelling is very weak and the benefits after total knee replacement surgery have been shown to be very small.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Adie |first1=S |last2=Kwan |first2=A |last3=Naylor |first3=JM |last4=Harris |first4=IA |last5=Mittal |first5=R |title=Cryotherapy following total knee replacement. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=12 September 2012 |issue=9 |pages=CD007911 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD007911.pub2 |pmid=22972114}}</ref>\n\nSome physicians and patients may consider having [[ultrasonography for deep venous thrombosis]] after knee replacement.<ref name=\"AAOSfive\">{{Citation |author1 = American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons |author1-link = American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons |date = February 2013 |title = Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question |publisher = American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons |work = [[Choosing Wisely]]: an initiative of the [[ABIM Foundation]] |page = |url = http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-academy-of-orthopaedic-surgeons/ |accessdate = 19 May 2013}}, which cites\n*{{cite journal |author=Members of 2007 and 2011 AAOS Guideline Development Work Groups on PE/VTED Prophylaxis |author2=Mont, M |author3=Jacobs, J |author4=Lieberman, J |author5=Parvizi, J |author6=Lachiewicz, P |author7=Johanson, N |author8= Watters, W  |title=Preventing venous thromboembolic disease in patients undergoing elective total hip and knee arthroplasty. |journal=The Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery. American Volume |date=18 April 2012 |volume=94 |issue=8 |pages=673\u20134 |pmid=22517384 |doi=10.2106/JBJS.9408edit |pmc=3326687}}</ref> However, this kind of screening should be done only when indicated because to perform it routinely would be [[unnecessary health care]].<ref name=\"AAOSfive\"/> If a medical condition exists that could cause deep vein thrombosis, a physician can choose to treat patients with [[cryotherapy]] and [[intermittent pneumatic compression]] as a preventive measure.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nNeither [[gabapentin]] nor [[pregabalin]] have been found to be useful for pain following a knee replacement.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hamilton|first1=TW|last2=Strickland|first2=LH|last3=Pandit|first3=HG|title=A Meta-Analysis on the Use of Gabapentinoids for the Treatment of Acute Postoperative Pain Following Total Knee Arthroplasty.|journal=The Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery. American Volume|date=17 August 2016|volume=98|issue=16|pages=1340\u201350|pmid=27535436|doi=10.2106/jbjs.15.01202}}</ref> A Cochrane review concluded that early multidisciplinary rehabilitation programs may produce better results at the rate of activity and participation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Khan|first=Fary|last2=Ng|first2=Louisa|last3=Gonzalez|first3=Senen|last4=Hale|first4=Tom|last5=Turner-Stokes|first5=Lynne|date=2008-04-23|title=Multidisciplinary rehabilitation programmes following joint replacement at the hip and knee in chronic arthropathy|journal=Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|issue=2|pages=CD004957|doi=10.1002/14651858.cd004957.pub3|pmid=18425906|issn=1465-1858}}</ref>\n\n==Frequency==\n\nWith 718,000 hospitalizations, knee arthroplasty accounted for 4.6% of all United States operating room procedures in 2011\u2014making it one of the most common procedures performed during hospital stays.<ref name=\"hcup-us.ahrq.gov\">Pfuntner A., Wier L.M., Stocks C. Most Frequent Procedures Performed in U.S. Hospitals, 2011. HCUP Statistical Brief #165. October 2013. Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality, Rockville, MD. [http://www.hcup-us.ahrq.gov/reports/statbriefs/sb165.jsp].</ref><ref>{{cite web |vauthors=Weiss AJ, Elixhauser A, Andrews RM | title = Characteristics of Operating Room Procedures in U.S. Hospitals, 2011. | work = HCUP Statistical Brief #170 | publisher = Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality | location = Rockville, MD | date = February 2014 | url = http://hcup-us.ahrq.gov/reports/statbriefs/sb170-Operating-Room-Procedures-United-States-2011.jsp }}</ref>  The number of knee arthroplasty procedures performed in U.S. hospitals increased 93% between 2001 and 2011.<ref>{{cite web |vauthors=Weiss AJ, Elixhauser A | title = Trends in Operating Room Procedures in U.S. Hospitals, 2001\u20142011. | work = HCUP Statistical Brief #171 | publisher = Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality | location = Rockville, MD | date = March 2014 | url = http://hcup-us.ahrq.gov/reports/statbriefs/sb171-Operating-Room-Procedure-Trends.jsp }}</ref> A study of United States community hospitals showed that in 2012, among hospitalizations that involved an OR procedure, knee arthroplasty was the OR procedure performed most frequently during hospital stays paid by Medicare (10.8 percent of stays) and by private insurance (9.1 percent). Knee arthroplasty was not among the top five most frequently performed OR procedures for stays paid by Medicaid or for uninsured stays.<ref>{{cite web |vauthors=Fingar KR, Stocks C, Weiss AJ, Steiner CA | title =  Most Frequent Operating Room Procedures Performed in U.S. Hospitals, 2003-2012 | work = HCUP Statistical Brief #186 | publisher = Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality | location = Rockville, MD | date = December 2014 | url =https://www.hcup-us.ahrq.gov/reports/statbriefs/sb186-Operating-Room-Procedures-United-States-2012.jsp}}</ref>\n\nBy 2030, the demand for primary total knee arthroplasty is projected to increase to 3.48 million surgeries performed annually in the U.S.<ref>{{cite journal | year = 2013 | title =  Essential amino acid supplementation in patients following total knee arthroplasty| journal = J Clin Invest | volume = 123 | issue = 11| pages = 4654\u20134666 | doi = 10.1172/JCI70160 | pmid=24135139 | pmc=3809795 |vauthors=Dreyer HC, Strycker LA, Senesac HA, Hocker AD, Smolkowski K, Shah SN, Jewett BA }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Autologous chondrocyte implantation]]\n* [[Microfracture surgery]]\n* [[Knee osteoarthritis]]\n* [[Osseointegration]]\n* [[Meniscus transplant]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/08/health/08brod.html A New Set of Knees Comes at a Price: A Whole Lot of Pain] By Jane E. Brody, The New York Times, 8 February 2005\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/15/health/15brod.html When It Comes to Severe Pain, Doctors Still Have Much to Learn] By Jane E. Brody, The New York Times, 15 February 2005\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/20/health/20brod.html A Year With My New Knees: Much Pain but Much Gain] By Jane E. Brody, The New York Times, 20 December 2005\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/03/health/03brod.html 3 Years Later, Knees Made for Dancing], By Jane E. Brody, The New York Times, 3 June 2008\n*[http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/09/relief-for-joints-besieged-by-arthritis/ Relief for Joints Besieged by Arthritis], By Jane E. Brody, The New York Times, 9 July 2012\n{{Medical resources}}\n{{Operations and other procedures on the musculoskeletal system}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knee Replacement}}\n[[Category:Implants (medicine)]]\n[[Category:Prosthetics]]\n[[Category:Orthopedic surgical procedures]]\n[[Category:Knee treatments|Replacement]]\n[[Category:Orthopedic implants]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "improve ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knee_replacement"}
{"title_page": "Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup rewrite|date=April 2020}}\n{{Notability|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society\n| abbreviation = CHCS\n| motto = \n| predecessor = \n| formation = 2018\n| founders = {{ubl | [[Ni\u00f1o Kevin D. Baclig]]}}\n| founding_location = [[Tuguegarao City]], Philippines\n| extinction = <!-- or: | dissolved = -->   <!--e.g. use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| merger = <!-- Other organizations (if any) merged to constitute the organization -->\n| type = [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]]\n| status = <!-- Organization's legal status and/or description (company, charity, foundation, etc) -->\n| purpose = Heritage conservation  <!--(humanitarian, activism, peacekeeping, etc)-->\n}}\n\nThe '''Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society''' is a non profit organization aimed at creating and spreading awareness about [[Cagayan|Cagaya]]<nowiki/>n's rich history and culture through cultural education & research, training, and policy reform.  It was founded in 2018 by [[Ni\u00f1o Kevin D. Baclig]], a native of [[Aparri]], Cagayan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1066477&ved=2ahUKEwjpmo7axMToAhULkJQKHTQYBlEQFjACegQIAhAB&usg=AOvVaw3rvbtCbRKt_bwu_hfuarae|title=500 join Heritage Walk in Tuguegarao|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://northernforum.net/who-said-cagayano-millennials-cant-revitalize-ibanag-itawes/|title=Who said Cagayano 'Millennials' can't revitalize Ibanag, Itawes?|last=Aquino|first=Amir|date=2018-08-23|website=The Northern Forum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nWith up to 100 active members in their mid-20s, they are poised to succeed elder local experts in the preservation of Cagayanos\u2019 languages and cultures later on.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Programs and Activities ==\nThe group is widely known for their successful heritage walks around [[Cagayan Valley]] dubbed as Manalan Tera. To date, they have conducted these informative walks in [[Aparri]], Tuguegarao City, Alcala, Dupax del Sur, and Bagabag. In Tuguegarao, The group's pioneers, President Kevin Baclig and Vice President Prince Wilson Macarubbo, gave lectures after the tour on old sites that included the East Central School, [[Tuguegarao Cathedral]], Rizal Park, Horno Ruins and Tribunal de Tuguegarao, which was the old provincial jail and now Cagayan Museum's new location. These sites have been proposed as heritage zone by the Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cagayan.gov.ph/news/heritage-walk-itinampok-ng-cagayan-museum-at-heritage-conservation-society/&ved=2ahUKEwjpmo7axMToAhULkJQKHTQYBlEQFjADegQIAxAB&usg=AOvVaw13im5BNY4yay-vaKxPsi2v|title=Heritage Walk itinampok ng Cagayan Museum at Heritage Conservation Society|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|language=Filipino}}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cagayan.gov.ph/news/heritage-walk-itinampok-ng-cagayan-museum-at-heritage-conservation-society/&ved=2ahUKEwi92P3igcnoAhXMEqYKHcbgDBQ4ChAWMAJ6BAgIEAE&usg=AOvVaw13im5BNY4yay-vaKxPsi2v|title=Heritage Walk itinampok ng Cagayan Museum at Heritage Conservation Society|last=Lucena|first=Gerard Josef|date=|website=Cagayan.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThey also involve themselves in  talents development and promotion with their Minas anna Zininag\u00e2 which is a stage for budding local poets and local composers and musicians. Talks and seminars are also conducted dubbed Y Zininaga Tam.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cagayan Valley]]\n* [[Cagayan Province]]\n* [[Ni\u00f1o Kevin D. Baclig]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Organizations based in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2018]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup rewrite|date=April 2020}}\n{{Notability|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society\n| abbreviation = CHCS\n| motto = \n| predecessor = \n| formation = 2018\n| founders = {{ubl | [[Ni\u00f1o Kevin D. Baclig]]}}\n| founding_location = [[Tuguegarao City]], Philippines\n| extinction = <!-- or: | dissolved = -->   <!--e.g. use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| merger = <!-- Other organizations (if any) merged to constitute the organization -->\n| type = [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]]\n| status = <!-- Organization's legal status and/or description (company, charity, foundation, etc) -->\n| purpose = Heritage conservation  <!--(humanitarian, activism, peacekeeping, etc)-->\n}}\n\nThe '''Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society''' is a non profit organization aimed at creating and spreading awareness about [[Cagayan|Cagaya]]<nowiki/>n's rich history and culture through cultural education & research, training, and policy reform.  It was founded in 2018 by [[Ni\u00f1o Kevin D. Baclig]], a native of [[Aparri]], Cagayan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1066477&ved=2ahUKEwjpmo7axMToAhULkJQKHTQYBlEQFjACegQIAhAB&usg=AOvVaw3rvbtCbRKt_bwu_hfuarae|title=500 join Heritage Walk in Tuguegarao|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}{{deadlink|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://northernforum.net/who-said-cagayano-millennials-cant-revitalize-ibanag-itawes/|title=Who said Cagayano 'Millennials' can't revitalize Ibanag, Itawes?|last=Aquino|first=Amir|date=2018-08-23|website=The Northern Forum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nWith up to 100 active members in their mid-20s, they are poised to succeed elder local experts in the preservation of Cagayanos\u2019 languages and cultures later on.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Programs and Activities ==\nThe group is widely known for their successful heritage walks around [[Cagayan Valley]] dubbed as Manalan Tera. To date, they have conducted these informative walks in [[Aparri]], Tuguegarao City, Alcala, Dupax del Sur, and Bagabag. In Tuguegarao, The group\u2019s pioneers, President Kevin Baclig and Vice President Prince Wilson Macarubbo, gave lectures after the tour on old sites that included the East Central School, [[Tuguegarao Cathedral]], Rizal Park, Horno Ruins and Tribunal de Tuguegarao, which was the old provincial jail and now Cagayan Museum\u2019s new location. These sites have been proposed as heritage zone by the Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cagayan.gov.ph/news/heritage-walk-itinampok-ng-cagayan-museum-at-heritage-conservation-society/&ved=2ahUKEwjpmo7axMToAhULkJQKHTQYBlEQFjADegQIAxAB&usg=AOvVaw13im5BNY4yay-vaKxPsi2v|title=Heritage Walk itinampok ng Cagayan Museum at Heritage Conservation Society|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|language=Filipino}}{{deadlink|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cagayan.gov.ph/news/heritage-walk-itinampok-ng-cagayan-museum-at-heritage-conservation-society/&ved=2ahUKEwi92P3igcnoAhXMEqYKHcbgDBQ4ChAWMAJ6BAgIEAE&usg=AOvVaw13im5BNY4yay-vaKxPsi2v|title=Heritage Walk itinampok ng Cagayan Museum at Heritage Conservation Society|last=Lucena|first=Gerard Josef|date=|website=Cagayan.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}{{deadlink|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThey also involve themselves in  talents development and promotion with their Minas anna Zininag\u00e2 which is a stage for budding local poets and local composers and musicians. Talks and seminars are also conducted dubbed Y Zininaga Tam.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cagayan Valley]]\n* [[Cagayan Province]]\n* [[Ni\u00f1o Kevin D. Baclig]]\n\n\n== References ==\n\n[[Category:Organizations based in the Philippines]]\n