{"title_page": "Old Mill High School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n|name           = Old Mill High School\n|image          =\n|established    = 1975\n|type           = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]], [[Secondary school|Secondary]]\n|district       = [[Anne Arundel County Public Schools]]\n|coordinates    = {{coord|39|7|22|N|76|37|42|W|region:US-MD_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n|grades         = 9-12\n|principal      =  Stacey Smith\n|enrollment     = 2,105 (September 2014)<ref>{{cite web|title=OFFICIAL ACTUAL SEPTEMBER 2014 ELEMENTARY ENROLLMENTS|url=http://www.aacps.org/html/schol/2014actual.pdf|publisher=Anne Arundel County Public Schools, Planning Office|date=5 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305012504/http://www.aacps.org/html/schol/2014actual.pdf|archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n|campus type = [[Suburban]]\n|colors         = Red, White, and Blue\n|mascot         = Patriot\n| rival= Arundel High School \n|location       = 600 Patriot Lane<br />[[Millersville, Maryland]]\n|website        = [https://www.aacps.org/Page/1240 AACPS website], [https://www.oldmillhs.org/m/ School website]\n}}\n\n'''Old Mill High School''' is an American public [[high school]] in [[Millersville, Maryland]] serving students in grades 9 through 12. It was occupied in 1975 and is administered by [[Anne Arundel County Public Schools]] (AACPS). The school was built to alleviate over-crowding at [[Arundel High School|Arundel]] and [[Severna Park High School|Severna Park]] High Schools. The school has no walls and no roofs in some classrooms, only partitions to separate their classrooms. Along with [[Annapolis High School (Maryland)|Annapolis High School]] and [[Meade Senior High School]], Old Mill Senior High is one of the three [[IB Diploma Programme|IB World Schools]] in [[Anne Arundel County]]. The school building also houses the high school's two feeder schools, Old Mill Middle School North and Old Mill Middle School South.  The school [[mascot]] is ''The Patriot''. Old Mill excels in academics{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}} as well as athletics, including on December 4, 2009 when Old Mill won the State Football Championship against Henry A. Wise, and on December 2, 2011  when Old Mill won the State Football Championship against Quince Orchard. While Old Mill's recent success in football is impressive it pales in comparison to Old Mill's consistent success on the wrestling mat. Old Mill is a perennial force on the wrestling mat with an impressive 9 State Championships (2009, 2007, 2003, 1995, 1993, 1992, 1991, 1990, 1989). Former Old Mill Head Wrestling Coach, Mike Hampe is in the National Hall of Fame and helped to build one of the most successful programs in the state of Maryland, if not the most successful. Old Mill also has major accomplishments in track & field and basketball. Old Mill's rivals are [[Arundel High School]] and [[Meade Senior High School|Meade High School]].\n\n==Academics==\nOld Mill High School is a public, magnet school located in Millersville, MD. It has 2,105 students in grades 9-12 with a student-teacher ratio of 16 to 1. According to state test scores, 92% of students are at least proficient in math and 91% in reading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.niche.com/k12/old-mill-high-school-millersville-md/|title=Explore Old Mill High School|website=Niche|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\nSince 1977,<ref>[http://www.css-msa.org/search.php?MODE=VIEW(MD133) CSS-MSA Status: Old Mill High School] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010233802/http://www.css-msa.org/search.php?MODE=VIEW(MD133)|date=October 10, 2007}}</ref> Old Mill has been accredited by the Commission on Secondary Schools of the [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools#Commissions on Elementary and Secondary Schools|Middle States Association]]. Newsweek Magazine also ranked Old Mill in their 2007 Top 1300 Public High Schools in the Country List, at #773.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.schooldigger.com/go/MD/schools/0006000109/school.aspx|title=Old Mill High|website=SchoolDigger|language=en|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\nOld Mill High School ranks 106th out of 170 schools in Maryland on School Digger. \n\n===International Baccalaureate (IB)===\nOld Mill High School has been an IB World School since April 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibo.org/school/002322/ |title=International Baccalaureate Organization (IBO) Old Mill High School |publisher=IBO |date= |accessdate=2014-03-08}}</ref> It offers the [[IB Diploma Programme]], preceded by the Extended Learning Program (ELP), or more commonly known as Pre-IB.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aacps.org/html/press/elp/elp.html |title=International Baccalaureate Program/Extended Learning Program (ELP) at Anne Arundel County Public Schools |publisher=Aacps.org |accessdate=2014-03-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140308180014/http://www.aacps.org/html/press/elp/elp.html |archive-date=2014-03-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The school offers a variety of standard level (SL) and higher level (HL) courses. The IB program is coordinated in Old Mill by Mrs. Sutherin and Mrs. Romanoski, and Ms. Klimes is the guidance counselor for all the IB students.\n\nOld Mill High School is currently an IB Middle Years Programme candidate school, with the intention being that Old Mill will be 'whole-school' International Baccalaureate eventually. This is in conjunction with the two other IB World Schools currently in place in Anne Arundel County, [[Annapolis High School (Maryland)|Annapolis High School]] and [[Meade Senior High School|Meade High School]].\n\n===Other Programs===\n*[[Advancement Via Individual Determination|AVID]]\n*[[English language learning and teaching|ESOL]]\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\nStudents at Old Mill Senior High School are encouraged to participate in extracurricular, community, social and professional development organizations including:\n*Student Government Association\n*Band\n*Chess Club\n*Chorus\n*Dance Company\n*[[FBLA]]\n*[[Future Homemakers of America|FHA]]\n*[[Language immersion#FLES|FLES]]/[[Language immersion#FLEX|FLEX]]\n*Foreign Language Club\n*Freshman Scholars\n*Gay-Straight Alliance\n*[[International Thespian Society]]\n*[[International ESOL Club]]\n*It's Academic\n*[[Junior Statesmen of America]]\n*[[Key Club]]\n*Ladies of Excellence\n*Literary Magazine (''Illuminations'')\n*Marching Band\n*Math Club\n*[[Mathematics Engineering and Science Achievement]]\n*Mock Trial\n*Model United Nations\n*Modern Music Masters Honor Society ([[Tri-M]])\n*Music Program (including color guard flags, concert band, jazz band, marching band, orchestra and stage band)\n*Musical Production\n*[[National Art Honor Society]]\n*[[National Honor Society]]\n*National Science Honor Society\n*[[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Honoraire de Fran\u00e7ais|National French Honor Society]]\n*[[Spanish Honor Society|National Spanish Honor Society]]\n*S.W.A.N. Club\n*Newspaper ([https://groups.yahoo.com/group/PatriotEcho/ ''The Patriot Echo''])\n*Patriots Achieving Total Success\n*Patriot Players Theatre Company (PPTC)\n*People for Animal Welfare\n*Photography Club\n*Junior Statesmen of America\n*TSA (Technology Student Association)\n*Pom Squad\n*Renaissance\n*Robotics Club\n*Salsa Club\n*Sailing Club\n*Shutter Society\n*Steel Drum Band\n*Video Game Production Club\n\n==Athletics==\nThe Old Mill Patriots participate in a variety of interscholastic sports and activities, including:\n\n===Fall===\n*[[Cheerleading]]\n*[[Cross Country Running]]\n*[[Field Hockey]]\n*[[American football|Football]] - 2009 Maryland 4A State Champions, 2011 Maryland 4A State Champions\n*[[Golf]]\n*[[Soccer]]\n*[[Volleyball]]\n\n===Winter===\n*[[Basketball]]\n*[[Bowling]]\n*[[Cheerleading]]\n*[[Indoor Track and Field]]\n*[[Scholastic wrestling|Wrestling]] 9x 3A/4A Maryland State Tournament Champions. 3x 3A/4A Maryland State Dual Champions. Former Coach Mike Hampe in the National Wrestling Hall of Fame.\n*[[swimming (sport)|Swimming]]\n*[[Tennis]]\n\n===Spring===\n*[[Baseball]] - 4X State Champion (1980, 1989, 2003, 2019)\n*[[Gymnastics]]\n*[[Lacrosse]]\n*[[Softball]]\n*[[Outdoor Track and Field]]\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Josh Hader]] (2012) - Baseball\n*Kai Dambach (2009) - Bundesliga broadcaster\n* [[Kevin Barnes (American football)|Kevin Barnes]] (2004) - American football player{{cn|date=November 2013}}\n* [[Jeong H. Kim]] (?1979?) founded Yurie Systems, president of Bell Labs<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1998-04-30/business/1998120005_1_kim-jeong-h-yurie |title=Yurie founder chases dreams |publisher=Baltimore Sun |date=1998-04-30 |accessdate=2014-03-08 |author=Mark Ribbing}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eng.umd.edu/facilities/kim-building-ataglance |title=The Jeong H. Kim Engineering Building: At A Glance |publisher=Eng.umd.edu |date= |accessdate=2014-03-08}}</ref>\n* [[Nick Kisner]] (2009) - Professional boxer\n* [[James E. Rzepkowski]] (1989) former member of [[Maryland House of Delegates]]{{cn|date=November 2013}}\n* [[Lester Speight]] (1981) - American football player, a professional wrestler and actor{{cn|date=November 2013}}\n* Roch Kubatko (1981) - Baltimore Sun, Mid-Atlantic Sports Network, MASNsports.com, MLB Network, 2-time Maryland Sportswriter of the Year (NSSA)\n\n==School staph infections==\nIn October 2007, Old Mill High School was listed as one of four high schools in Anne Arundel County that had outbreaks of staph infections.  28 cases of the infection have also been reported at [[Severna Park High School]], [[Glen Burnie High School]], and [[Chesapeake High School, Anne Arundel County|Chesapeake High School]].<ref>[http://wbal.com/news/story.asp?articleid=64146 WBAL News]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.oldmillhs.org/ Website maintained by the school]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060528195443/http://www.aacps.org/html/schol/High/Oldmhs.asp AACPS webpage for Old Mill High]\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Maryland]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1975]]\n[[Category:Schools in Anne Arundel County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:1975 establishments in Maryland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n|name           = Old Mill High School\n|image          =\n|established    = 1975\n|type           = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]], [[Secondary school|Secondary]]\n|district       = [[Anne Arundel County Public Schools]]\n|coordinates    = {{coord|39|7|22|N|76|37|42|W|region:US-MD_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n|grades         = 9-12\n|principal      =  Stacey Smith\n|enrollment     = 2,105 (September 2014)<ref>{{cite web|title=OFFICIAL ACTUAL SEPTEMBER 2014 ELEMENTARY ENROLLMENTS|url=http://www.aacps.org/html/schol/2014actual.pdf|publisher=Anne Arundel County Public Schools, Planning Office|date=5 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305012504/http://www.aacps.org/html/schol/2014actual.pdf|archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n|campus type = [[Suburban]]\n|colors         = Red, White, and Blue\n|mascot         = Patriot\n| rival= Arundel High School \n|location       = 600 Patriot Lane<br />[[Millersville, Maryland]]\n|website        = [https://www.aacps.org/Page/1240 AACPS website], [https://www.oldmillhs.org/m/ School website]\n}}\n\n'''Old Mill High School''' is an American public [[high school]] in [[Millersville, Maryland]] serving students in grades 9 through 12. It was occupied in 1975 and is administered by [[Anne Arundel County Public Schools]] (AACPS). The school was built to alleviate over-crowding at [[Arundel High School|Arundel]] and [[Severna Park High School|Severna Park]] High Schools. The school has no walls and no roofs in some classrooms, only partitions to separate their classrooms. Along with [[Annapolis High School (Maryland)|Annapolis High School]] and [[Meade Senior High School]], Old Mill Senior High is one of the three [[IB Diploma Programme|IB World Schools]] in [[Anne Arundel County]]. The school building also houses the high school's two feeder schools, Old Mill Middle School North and Old Mill Middle School South.  The school [[mascot]] is ''The Patriot''. Old Mill excels in academics{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}} as well as athletics, including on December 4, 2009 when Old Mill won the State Football Championship against Henry A. Wise, and on December 2, 2011  when Old Mill won the State Football Championship against Quince Orchard. While Old Mill's recent success in football is impressive it pales in comparison to Old Mill's consistent success on the wrestling mat. Old Mill is a perennial force on the wrestling mat with an impressive 9 State Championships (2009, 2007, 2003, 1995, 1993, 1992, 1991, 1990, 1989). Former Old Mill Head Wrestling Coach, Mike Hampe is in the National Hall of Fame and helped to build one of the most successful programs in the state of Maryland, if not the most successful. Old Mill also has major accomplishments in track & field and basketball. Old Mill's rivals are [[Arundel High School]] and [[Meade Senior High School|Meade High School]].\n\n==Academics==\nOld Mill High School is a public, magnet school located in Millersville, MD. It has 2,105 students in grades 9-12 with a student-teacher ratio of 16 to 1. According to state test scores, 92% of students are at least proficient in math and 91% in reading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.niche.com/k12/old-mill-high-school-millersville-md/|title=Explore Old Mill High School|website=Niche|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\nSince 1977,<ref>[http://www.css-msa.org/search.php?MODE=VIEW(MD133) CSS-MSA Status: Old Mill High School] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010233802/http://www.css-msa.org/search.php?MODE=VIEW(MD133)|date=October 10, 2007}}</ref> Old Mill has been accredited by the Commission on Secondary Schools of the [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools#Commissions on Elementary and Secondary Schools|Middle States Association]]. Newsweek Magazine also ranked Old Mill in their 2007 Top 1300 Public High Schools in the Country List, at #773.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.schooldigger.com/go/MD/schools/0006000109/school.aspx|title=Old Mill High|website=SchoolDigger|language=en|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\nOld Mill High School ranks 106th out of 170 schools in Maryland on School Digger. \n\n===International Baccalaureate (IB)===\nOld Mill High School has been an IB World School since April 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibo.org/school/002322/ |title=International Baccalaureate Organization (IBO) Old Mill High School |publisher=IBO |date= |accessdate=2014-03-08}}</ref> It offers the [[IB Diploma Programme]], preceded by the Extended Learning Program (ELP), or more commonly known as Pre-IB.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aacps.org/html/press/elp/elp.html |title=International Baccalaureate Program/Extended Learning Program (ELP) at Anne Arundel County Public Schools |publisher=Aacps.org |accessdate=2014-03-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140308180014/http://www.aacps.org/html/press/elp/elp.html |archive-date=2014-03-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The school offers a variety of standard level (SL) and higher level (HL) courses. The IB program is coordinated in Old Mill by Mrs. Sutherin and Mrs. Romanoski, and Ms. Klimes is the guidance counselor for all the IB students.\n\nOld Mill High School is currently an IB Middle Years Programme candidate school, with the intention being that Old Mill will be 'whole-school' International Baccalaureate eventually. This is in conjunction with the two other IB World Schools currently in place in Anne Arundel County, [[Annapolis High School (Maryland)|Annapolis High School]] and [[Meade Senior High School|Meade High School]].\n\n===Other Programs===\n*[[Advancement Via Individual Determination|AVID]]\n*[[English language learning and teaching|ESOL]]\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\nStudents at Old Mill Senior High School are encouraged to participate in extracurricular, community, social and professional development organizations including:\n*Student Government Association\n*Band\n*Chess Club\n*Chorus\n*Dance Company\n*[[FBLA]]\n*[[Future Homemakers of America|FHA]]\n*[[Language immersion#FLES|FLES]]/[[Language immersion#FLEX|FLEX]]\n*Foreign Language Club\n*Freshman Scholars\n*Gay-Straight Alliance\n*[[International Thespian Society]]\n*[[International ESOL Club]]\n*It's Academic\n*[[Junior Statesmen of America]]\n*[[Key Club]]\n*Ladies of Excellence\n*Literary Magazine (''Illuminations'')\n*Marching Band\n*Math Club\n*[[Mathematics Engineering and Science Achievement]]\n*Mock Trial\n*Model United Nations\n*Modern Music Masters Honor Society ([[Tri-M]])\n*Music Program (including color guard flags, concert band, jazz band, marching band, orchestra and stage band)\n*Musical Production\n*[[National Art Honor Society]]\n*[[National Honor Society]]\n*National Science Honor Society\n*[[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Honoraire de Fran\u00e7ais|National French Honor Society]]\n*[[Spanish Honor Society|National Spanish Honor Society]]\n*S.W.A.N. Club\n*Newspaper ([https://groups.yahoo.com/group/PatriotEcho/ ''The Patriot Echo''])\n*Patriots Achieving Total Success\n*Patriot Players Theatre Company (PPTC)\n*People for Animal Welfare\n*Photography Club\n*Junior Statesmen of America\n*TSA (Technology Student Association)\n*Pom Squad\n*Renaissance\n*Robotics Club\n*Salsa Club\n*Sailing Club\n*Shutter Society\n*Steel Drum Band\n*Video Game Production Club\n\n==Athletics==\nThe Old Mill Patriots participate in a variety of interscholastic sports and activities, including:\n\n===Fall===\n*[[Cheerleading]]\n*[[Cross Country Running]]\n*[[Field Hockey]]\n*[[American football|Football]] - 2009 Maryland 4A State Champions, 2011 Maryland 4A State Champions\n*[[Golf]]\n*[[Soccer]]\n*[[Volleyball]]\n\n===Winter===\n*[[Basketball]]\n*[[Bowling]]\n*[[Cheerleading]]\n*[[Indoor Track and Field]]\n*[[Scholastic wrestling|Wrestling]] 9x 3A/4A Maryland State Tournament Champions. 3x 3A/4A Maryland State Dual Champions. Former Coach Mike Hampe in the National Wrestling Hall of Fame.\n*[[swimming (sport)|Swimming]]\n*[[Tennis]]\n\n===Spring===\n*[[Baseball]] - 4X State Champion (1980, 1989, 2003, 2019)\n*[[Gymnastics]]\n*[[Lacrosse]]\n*[[Softball]]\n*[[Outdoor Track and Field]]\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Josh Hader]] (2012) - Baseball\n* [[Kevin Barnes (American football)|Kevin Barnes]] (2004) - American football player{{cn|date=November 2013}}\n* [[Jeong H. Kim]] (?1979?) founded Yurie Systems, president of Bell Labs<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1998-04-30/business/1998120005_1_kim-jeong-h-yurie |title=Yurie founder chases dreams |publisher=Baltimore Sun |date=1998-04-30 |accessdate=2014-03-08 |author=Mark Ribbing}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eng.umd.edu/facilities/kim-building-ataglance |title=The Jeong H. Kim Engineering Building: At A Glance |publisher=Eng.umd.edu |date= |accessdate=2014-03-08}}</ref>\n* [[Nick Kisner]] (2009) - Professional boxer\n* [[James E. Rzepkowski]] (1989) former member of [[Maryland House of Delegates]]{{cn|date=November 2013}}\n* [[Lester Speight]] (1981) - American football player, a professional wrestler and actor{{cn|date=November 2013}}\n* Roch Kubatko (1981) - Baltimore Sun, Mid-Atlantic Sports Network, MASNsports.com, MLB Network, 2-time Maryland Sportswriter of the Year (NSSA)\n\n==School staph infections==\nIn October 2007, Old Mill High School was listed as one of four high schools in Anne Arundel County that had outbreaks of staph infections.  28 cases of the infection have also been reported at [[Severna Park High School]], [[Glen Burnie High School]], and [[Chesapeake High School, Anne Arundel County|Chesapeake High School]].<ref>[http://wbal.com/news/story.asp?articleid=64146 WBAL News]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.oldmillhs.org/ Website maintained by the school]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060528195443/http://www.aacps.org/html/schol/High/Oldmhs.asp AACPS webpage for Old Mill High]\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Maryland]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1975]]\n[[Category:Schools in Anne Arundel County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:1975 establishments in Maryland]]\n", "name_user": "Bundesligafanatic1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable alumni:included an international sports commentator that graduated from the school", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Mill_High_School"}
{"title_page": "Trajan's Forum", "text_new": "{{Ancient monuments in Rome\n|name=Trajan's Forum\n|label_name=Trajan's Forum\n|image_name=ForumRomanumRoma.jpg\n|caption=\n|coordinates = {{coord|41|53|44|N|12|29|09|E|type:landmark_region:IT|display=inline}}\n|location=[[14 regions of Augustan Rome|IV Templum Pacis'']]\n|date=106\u2013112 AD\n|builder=[[Trajan|Emperor Trajan]]\n|type=[[Imperial fora]]\n|wiki articles=[[Quirinal|Quirinal Hill]], [[Capitoline Hill]], [[Trajan's Column]], [[Trajan's Market]]\n}}\n'''Trajan's Forum''' ({{lang-la|Forum Traiani}}; {{lang-it|Foro di Traiano}}) was the last of the [[Imperial fora]] to be constructed in ancient [[Rome]].<ref name=roth>{{cite book | first=Leland M. | last=Roth | year=1993 | title=Understanding Architecture: Its Elements, History and Meaning | edition=First | publisher=Westview Press | location=Boulder, CO | isbn=0-06-430158-3 | pages= | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/understandingarc00roth }}</ref> The architect [[Apollodorus of Damascus]] oversaw its construction.\n\n==History==\n\nThis forum was built on the order of the emperor [[Trajan]] with the [[War looting|spoils of war]] from the conquest of [[Dacia]], which ended in 106.<ref name=\"roth\"/> The construction began between 105 and 107<ref name=\"Carandini\">{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=176}}</ref>; according to the ''[[Fasti Ostienses]]'' the Forum was inaugurated in 112. [[Trajan's Column]] was erected and then inaugurated in 113.\n\nTo build this monumental complex, extensive excavations were required: workers eliminated a ridge connecting the [[Quirinal]] and [[Capitoline Hill|Capitoline]] (Campidoglio) Hills. Over 300,000 cubic meters of soil and rock were excavated and dumped outside the [[Porta Collina]].<ref name=\"Carandini\"/><ref>{{cite book| title=The Ruins and Excavations of Ancient Rome| author=Rodolfo Lanciani| publisher=Houghton Mifflin| year=1897| p=312}}</ref>\n\nIt is possible that the excavations were initiated under [[Domitian|Emperor Domitian]], while the project of the Forum was completely attributed to the architect [[Apollodorus of Damascus]],<ref name=roth/> who also accompanied Emperor Trajan in the Dacian campaign.\n\nDuring the time of the construction, several other projects took place: the construction of the [[Markets of Trajan]],<ref name=roth/> and the renovation of the [[Caesar's Forum]] (where the [[Basilica Argentaria]] was built)  and the [[Temple of Venus Genetrix]].\n\n==Structure==\nThe Forum consisted of a sequence of open and enclosed spaces, beginning with the vast [[portico]]-lined [[piazza]] measuring {{convert|300|m|ft|abbr=off}} long and {{convert|185|m|ft|abbr=off}} wide, with ''[[exedra]]e'' on two sides. The main entrance is at the north end of the piazza, which was cobbled with rectangular blocks of white [[marble]] and decorated by a large equestrian statue of Trajan. On either side of the piazza are markets, also housed by the exedrae. The open space of the Forum measured about 300 feet by 380 feet.<ref>Fritz Heichelheim, Cedric Veo, Allan Ward(1984);A History of the Roman People; Prentice-Hall; Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey</ref> Originally, the forum was enclosed within high walls built from blocks of [[Peperino]] tuff, covered with a marble veneer, similar to those used to enclose the fora of [[Forum of Augustus| Augustus]] and [[Forum of Nerva| Nerva]].<ref>{{cite book| title=The Ruins and Excavations of Ancient Rome| author=Rodolfo Lanciani| publisher=Houghton Mifflin| year=1897| p=312-13}}</ref> Via a doorway in the far east wall of the Forum, one gained entry to an open courtyard with a portico, which communicated in turn with the neighboring Forum of Augustus.<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=176}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Trajan forum.jpg|thumb|Plan of Trajan's Forum]]\nAlong the piazza's north side was the [[Basilica Ulpia]], and north of that was a smaller piazza, with a [[temple of Trajan|temple dedicated to the deified Trajan]] on the far north side facing inwards. The position of - and very existence of - the temple dedicated to the deified Trajan is a matter of hotly contested debate among archaeologists, particularly clear in the ongoing debate between James E. Packer and Roberto Meneghini.<ref>J. E. Packer and J. Burge, \u201cTemplum Divi Traiani Parthici et Plotinae: a debate with R. Meneghini,\u201d ''Journal of Roman Archaeology'' (January 2003) pp. 103-136.</ref> Between the Basilica Ulpia and the terminal piazza containing the temple, were two libraries, one housing Latin documents and the other Greek documents.  Between the libraries stood the {{convert|38|m|ft|adj=mid|abbr=off}} [[Trajan's Column]].<ref name=roth/> The libraries housed state archives including the acts of the Emperors and the edicts of the [[praetors]].<ref>{{cite article| url=https://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Forum_Trajani.html#basilica_Ulpia| title=A Topographical Dictionary of Ancient Rome| authors=Samuel B. Platner & Thomas Ashby| publisher=Oxford University Press| year=1929| p=237-245}}</ref>\n\nTrajan's successor [[Hadrian]] added a philosophical school adjacent to the piazza containing the Temple of Trajan. The building consisted of three parallel halls separated by annexes and was known as the ''Athenaeum''; it functioned variously as school, a venue for judicial proceedings, and an occasional meeting-place for the Senate.<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=177}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Platner-fora-imperial-96a Recontructed.jpg|thumb|Map of the Imperial Fora showing Trajan's Forum]]\n[[Constantius II]], while visiting Rome in the year 357,<ref name=guide>{{cite book | title = Archaeological Guide to Rome | publisher = Electa | editor-last = La Regina | editor-first = Adriano | orig-year = 2004 | edition = New update | year = 2007 | others = Richard Sadleir (trans.) | page=188}}</ref> was amazed by the huge equestrian statue of Trajan and by the surrounding buildings:\n\n{{quote|text=But when he [Constantius II] came to the Forum of Trajan, a construction unique under the heavens, as we believe, and admirable even in the unanimous opinion of the gods, he stood fast in amazement, turning his attention to the gigantic complex about him, beggaring description and never again to be imitated by mortal men. So renouncing all hope of attempting anything of the kind, he said he wanted to imitate only Trajan's horse, set in the middle of the atrium, and with the emperor on its back. And prince Ormisda ... standing beside him, replied with pleasing wit: \"First, emperor, command the construction of a stable like this, so that the horse you wish to have made can find as appropriate a setting as that we have before our eyes.\"| sign = [[Ammianus Marcellinus]] | source = Histories XVI.10.15-16<ref name=guide /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/16*.html |title=Ammianus Marcellinus Roman Antiquities  |publisher=penelope.uchicago.edu |accessdate=1 December 2010}}</ref>}}\n\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right | headerimage=[[File:073ForoTraiano.jpg|210px]] | video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y-IAOPxkNWo Trajan's Forum], [[Smarthistory]] at [[Khan Academy]] (6:00), December 1, 2014 }}\n\nIn modern times only a section of the markets and the column of Trajan remain. A number of columns which historically formed the Basilica Ulpia remained on site, and have been re-erected. The construction of the [[Via dei Fori Imperiali]] in 1933 covered a number of these columns, which remain visible under the arches on which the road runs.\n\n==Post-Roman history==\nIn the mid-9th century, the marble cobble blocks of the piazza were systematically taken for re-use, because of the good quality of the lime. They were replaced with concrete, showing that the piazza was still in use as a public space.\n\n[[File:Trajan's Forum at night.jpg|thumb|Trajan's Forum at night]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Imperial fora]]\n*[[List of Roman domes]]\n*[[Roman architecture]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|first=James|last= Packer|title=  Trajan\u2019s Forum: A Study of the Monuments|publisher= University of California Press|year= 1997}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Trajan's Forum (Rome)}}\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/imperial_fora_of_rome/2517676103/in/set-72157600215755762/ Roma \u2013 I Fori Imperiali (1995-2008). The Forum of Trajan. Excavations & Related studies (1998-2008). Prof. James. E. Packer, (ed. it.), Il Foro di Traiano a Roma. Breve studio dei monumenti (Roma 2001).]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/imperial_fora_of_rome/6140219014/in/set-72157600215755762 Rome, Archaeology News: The Reappearance of the Temple of Trajan & The Athenaeum in Rome (September 2011).]\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Forum Traiani |short=x}}\n*High-resolution 360\u00b0 Panoramas and Images of [https://mcid.mcah.columbia.edu/art-atlas/ancient-and-early-christian-sites-rome/forum-trajan Trajan's Forum | Art Atlas]\n\n{{coord|41|53|44|N|12|29|09|E|region:IT_type:landmark|display=title}}\n{{Imperial forums of Rome}}\n{{Monuments of Rome}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n\n[[Category:Trajan's Forum| ]]\n[[Category:Imperial forums of Rome]]\n[[Category:Rome R. I Monti]]\n[[Category:Trajan|Forum]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in the 2nd century]]\n[[Category:110s establishments in the Roman Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Ancient monuments in Rome\n|name=Trajan's Forum\n|label_name=Trajan's Forum\n|image_name=ForumRomanumRoma.jpg\n|caption=\n|coordinates = {{coord|41|53|44|N|12|29|09|E|type:landmark_region:IT|display=inline}}\n|location=[[14 regions of Augustan Rome|IV Templum Pacis'']]\n|date=106\u2013112 AD\n|builder=[[Trajan|Emperor Trajan]]\n|type=[[Imperial fora]]\n|wiki articles=[[Quirinal|Quirinal Hill]], [[Capitoline Hill]], [[Trajan's Column]], [[Trajan's Market]]\n}}\n'''Trajan's Forum''' ({{lang-la|Forum Traiani}}; {{lang-it|Foro di Traiano}}) was the last of the [[Imperial fora]] to be constructed in ancient [[Rome]].<ref name=roth>{{cite book | first=Leland M. | last=Roth | year=1993 | title=Understanding Architecture: Its Elements, History and Meaning | edition=First | publisher=Westview Press | location=Boulder, CO | isbn=0-06-430158-3 | pages= | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/understandingarc00roth }}</ref> The architect [[Apollodorus of Damascus]] oversaw its construction.\n\n==History==\n\nThis forum was built on the order of the emperor [[Trajan]] with the [[War looting|spoils of war]] from the conquest of [[Dacia]], which ended in 106.<ref name=\"roth\"/> The construction began between 105 and 107<ref name=\"Carandini\">{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=176}}</ref>; according to the ''[[Fasti Ostienses]]'' the Forum was inaugurated in 112. [[Trajan's Column]] was erected and then inaugurated in 113.\n\nTo build this monumental complex, extensive excavations were required: workers eliminated a ridge connecting the [[Quirinal]] and [[Capitoline Hill|Capitoline]] (Campidoglio) Hills. Over 300,000 cubic meters of soil and rock were excavated and dumped outside the [[Porta Collina]].<ref name=\"Carandini\"/><ref>{{cite book| title=The Ruins and Excavations of Ancient Rome| author=Rodolfo Lanciani| publisher=Houghton Mifflin| year=1897| p=312}}</ref>\n\nIt is possible that the excavations were initiated under [[Domitian|Emperor Domitian]], while the project of the Forum was completely attributed to the architect [[Apollodorus of Damascus]],<ref name=roth/> who also accompanied Emperor Trajan in the Dacian campaign.\n\nDuring the time of the construction, several other projects took place: the construction of the [[Markets of Trajan]],<ref name=roth/> and the renovation of the [[Caesar's Forum]] (where the [[Basilica Argentaria]] was built)  and the [[Temple of Venus Genetrix]].\n\n==Structure==\nThe Forum consisted of a sequence of open and enclosed spaces, beginning with the vast [[portico]]-lined [[piazza]] measuring {{convert|300|m|ft|abbr=off}} long and {{convert|185|m|ft|abbr=off}} wide, with ''[[exedra]]e'' on two sides. The main entrance is at the north end of the piazza, which was cobbled with rectangular blocks of white [[marble]] and decorated by a large equestrian statue of Trajan. On either side of the piazza are markets, also housed by the exedrae. The open space of the Forum measured about 300 feet by 380 feet.<ref>Fritz Heichelheim, Cedric Veo, Allan Ward(1984);A History of the Roman People; Prentice-Hall; Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey</ref> Originally, the forum was enclosed within high walls built from blocks of [[Peperino]] tuff, covered with a marble veneer, similar to those used to enclose the fora of [[Forum of Augustus| Augustus]] and [[Forum of Nerva| Nerva]].<ref>{{cite book| title=The Ruins and Excavations of Ancient Rome| author=Rodolfo Lanciani| publisher=Houghton Mifflin| year=1897| p=312-13}}</ref> Via the wall on the far east side of Trajan's Forum, where there was a doorway which led into a communicating annex, one could gain entry into the neighboring Forum of Augustus, and vice versa.<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=176}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Trajan forum.jpg|thumb|Plan of Trajan's Forum]]\nAlong the piazza's north side was the [[Basilica Ulpia]], and north of that was a smaller piazza, with a [[temple of Trajan|temple dedicated to the deified Trajan]] on the far north side facing inwards. The position of - and very existence of - the temple dedicated to the deified Trajan is a matter of hotly contested debate among archaeologists, particularly clear in the ongoing debate between James E. Packer and Roberto Meneghini.<ref>J. E. Packer and J. Burge, \u201cTemplum Divi Traiani Parthici et Plotinae: a debate with R. Meneghini,\u201d ''Journal of Roman Archaeology'' (January 2003) pp. 103-136.</ref> Between the Basilica Ulpia and the terminal piazza containing the temple, were two libraries, one housing Latin documents and the other Greek documents.  Between the libraries stood the {{convert|38|m|ft|adj=mid|abbr=off}} [[Trajan's Column]].<ref name=roth/> The libraries housed state archives including the acts of the Emperors and the edicts of the [[praetors]].<ref>{{cite article| url=https://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Forum_Trajani.html#basilica_Ulpia| title=A Topographical Dictionary of Ancient Rome| authors=Samuel B. Platner & Thomas Ashby| publisher=Oxford University Press| year=1929| p=237-245}}</ref>\n\nTrajan's successor [[Hadrian]] added a philosophical school adjacent to the piazza containing the Temple of Trajan. The building consisted of three parallel halls separated by annexes and was known as the ''Athenaeum''; it functioned variously as school, a venue for judicial proceedings, and an occasional meeting-place for the Senate.<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=177}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Platner-fora-imperial-96a Recontructed.jpg|thumb|Map of the Imperial Fora showing Trajan's Forum]]\n[[Constantius II]], while visiting Rome in the year 357,<ref name=guide>{{cite book | title = Archaeological Guide to Rome | publisher = Electa | editor-last = La Regina | editor-first = Adriano | orig-year = 2004 | edition = New update | year = 2007 | others = Richard Sadleir (trans.) | page=188}}</ref> was amazed by the huge equestrian statue of Trajan and by the surrounding buildings:\n\n{{quote|text=But when he [Constantius II] came to the Forum of Trajan, a construction unique under the heavens, as we believe, and admirable even in the unanimous opinion of the gods, he stood fast in amazement, turning his attention to the gigantic complex about him, beggaring description and never again to be imitated by mortal men. So renouncing all hope of attempting anything of the kind, he said he wanted to imitate only Trajan's horse, set in the middle of the atrium, and with the emperor on its back. And prince Ormisda ... standing beside him, replied with pleasing wit: \"First, emperor, command the construction of a stable like this, so that the horse you wish to have made can find as appropriate a setting as that we have before our eyes.\"| sign = [[Ammianus Marcellinus]] | source = Histories XVI.10.15-16<ref name=guide /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/16*.html |title=Ammianus Marcellinus Roman Antiquities  |publisher=penelope.uchicago.edu |accessdate=1 December 2010}}</ref>}}\n\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right | headerimage=[[File:073ForoTraiano.jpg|210px]] | video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y-IAOPxkNWo Trajan's Forum], [[Smarthistory]] at [[Khan Academy]] (6:00), December 1, 2014 }}\n\nIn modern times only a section of the markets and the column of Trajan remain. A number of columns which historically formed the Basilica Ulpia remained on site, and have been re-erected. The construction of the [[Via dei Fori Imperiali]] in 1933 covered a number of these columns, which remain visible under the arches on which the road runs.\n\n==Post-Roman history==\nIn the mid-9th century, the marble cobble blocks of the piazza were systematically taken for re-use, because of the good quality of the lime. They were replaced with concrete, showing that the piazza was still in use as a public space.\n\n[[File:Trajan's Forum at night.jpg|thumb|Trajan's Forum at night]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Imperial fora]]\n*[[List of Roman domes]]\n*[[Roman architecture]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|first=James|last= Packer|title=  Trajan\u2019s Forum: A Study of the Monuments|publisher= University of California Press|year= 1997}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Trajan's Forum (Rome)}}\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/imperial_fora_of_rome/2517676103/in/set-72157600215755762/ Roma \u2013 I Fori Imperiali (1995-2008). The Forum of Trajan. Excavations & Related studies (1998-2008). Prof. James. E. Packer, (ed. it.), Il Foro di Traiano a Roma. Breve studio dei monumenti (Roma 2001).]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/imperial_fora_of_rome/6140219014/in/set-72157600215755762 Rome, Archaeology News: The Reappearance of the Temple of Trajan & The Athenaeum in Rome (September 2011).]\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Forum Traiani |short=x}}\n*High-resolution 360\u00b0 Panoramas and Images of [https://mcid.mcah.columbia.edu/art-atlas/ancient-and-early-christian-sites-rome/forum-trajan Trajan's Forum | Art Atlas]\n\n{{coord|41|53|44|N|12|29|09|E|region:IT_type:landmark|display=title}}\n{{Imperial forums of Rome}}\n{{Monuments of Rome}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n\n[[Category:Trajan's Forum| ]]\n[[Category:Imperial forums of Rome]]\n[[Category:Rome R. I Monti]]\n[[Category:Trajan|Forum]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in the 2nd century]]\n[[Category:110s establishments in the Roman Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Volubilis90", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStructure", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trajan%27s_Forum"}
{"title_page": "Patrick Lyon, 3rd Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| pre-nominals = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne\n| image = Patrick Lyon, 3rd Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne.png\n| caption = Patrick Lyon, 3rd Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne\n| birth_date = 29 May 1643\n| death_date = 15 May 1695\n| nationality = Scottish\n| title = 3rd [[Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne]]\n| spouse = Helen Middleton\n| children = 8 (including [[John Lyon, 4th Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne]] and [[Patrick Lyon of Auchterhouse|Patrick Lyon]])\n| parents = [[John Lyon, 2nd Earl of Kinghorne]]<br>Lady Elizabeth Maule\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Lyon, 3rd Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne''' (29 May 1643 \u2013 15 May 1695) was a [[Peerage of Scotland|Scottish peer]] and nobleman. He was the son of [[John Lyon, 2nd Earl of Kinghorne]] and his wife Lady Elizabeth Maule, daughter of [[Patrick Maule, 1st Earl of Panmure]] and Frances Stanhope. Patrick was the grandson of [[Patrick Lyon, 1st Earl of Kinghorne]] and his wife [[Anne Lyon, Countess of Kinghorne|Anne Murray]].\n\n==Life==\nOn 12 May 1646, 17 days before his third birthday, Patrick inherited the titles of third Earl of Kinghorne and eleventh Lord Glamis from his father, as well as [[Glamis Castle]] and Castle Lyon (now [[Castle Huntly]]), which had been purchased by 1st [[Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne|Earl of Kinghorne]] in 1614. On 30 May 1672 he obtained a new charter, ratified in Parliament on 1 July 1677, giving an addition to his title, which was in future to be Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne, Viscount Lyon, Lord Glammis, Tannadyce, Sidlaw, and Stradichtie, with the precedence of the former honour of Earl of Kinghorne.\n\n==Family==\nPatrick Lyon married Helen Middleton, daughter of [[John Middleton, 1st Earl of Middleton]], and his wife Grizel Durham, on 23 August 1662. They had issue:\n\n#[[John Lyon, 4th Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne]] (8 May 1663&ndash;10 May 1712).\n#Lady Grizel Lyon (1665&ndash;circa 1721)  married [[David Ogilvy, 3rd Earl of Airlie]], and had issue.\n#Lady Jean Lyon (1666&ndash;unknown), died young.\n#Lady Elizabeth Lyon (1666&ndash;before 1672), died young.\n#[[Patrick Lyon of Auchterhouse|Patrick Lyon]] (1669&ndash;1715).\n#Lady Elizabeth Lyon (1672&ndash;1739), married [[Charles Gordon, 1st Earl of Aboyne]], and had issue, married [[Patrick Kinnaird, 3rd Lord Kinnaird]], had issue, married Capt. Alexander Grant, no issue.\n#Lady Adelaide Lyon (1676\u20131698){{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}.\n#Charles Lyon (1679&ndash;1692), died young.\n\n==References==\n*{{cite DNB|wstitle=Lyon, Patrick (1642-1695)}}\n*{{cite book|last=Balfour Paul|first=Sir James|authorlink=James Balfour Paul|title=The Scots peerage|url=https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun08pauluoft|volume=XIII|year=1904 |publisher=D. Douglas |location=Edinburgh|pages=299\u2013303}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-reg|sct}}\n{{succession box |title=[[Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne]] | before=[[John Lyon, 2nd Earl of Kinghorne|John Lyon]]\n(as ''Earl of Kinghorne'')| after=[[John Lyon, 4th Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne|John Lyon]]|years=}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strathmore and Kinghorne, Patrick Lyon, 3rd Earl of}}\n[[Category:1643 births]]\n[[Category:1695 deaths]]\n[[Category:Earls of Strathmore and Kinghorne|3]]\n[[Category:Clan Lyon|Patrick]]\n[[Category:Extraordinary Lords of Session]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish peers]]\n\n{{Scotland-earl-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| pre-nominals = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne\n| image = Patrick Lyon, 3rd Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne.png\n| caption = Patrick Lyon, 3rd Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne\n| birth_date = 29 May 1643\n| death_date = 15 May 1695\n| nationality = Scottish\n| title = 3rd [[Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne]]\n| spouse = Helen Middleton\n| children = 8 (including [[John Lyon, 4th Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne]] and [[Patrick Lyon of Auchterhouse|Patrick Lyon]])\n| parents = [[John Lyon, 2nd Earl of Kinghorne]]<br>Lady Elizabeth Maule\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Lyon, 3rd Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne''' (29 May 1643 \u2013 15 May 1695) was a [[Peerage of Scotland|Scottish peer]] and nobleman. He was the son of [[John Lyon, 2nd Earl of Kinghorne]] and his wife Lady Elizabeth Maule, daughter of [[Patrick Maule, 1st Earl of Panmure]] and Frances Stanhope. Patrick was the grandson of [[Patrick Lyon, 1st Earl of Kinghorne]] and his wife Lady Anne Murray.\n\n==Life==\nOn 12 May 1646, 17 days before his third birthday, Patrick inherited the titles of third Earl of Kinghorne and eleventh Lord Glamis from his father, as well as [[Glamis Castle]] and Castle Lyon (now [[Castle Huntly]]), which had been purchased by 1st [[Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne|Earl of Kinghorne]] in 1614. On 30 May 1672 he obtained a new charter, ratified in Parliament on 1 July 1677, giving an addition to his title, which was in future to be Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne, Viscount Lyon, Lord Glammis, Tannadyce, Sidlaw, and Stradichtie, with the precedence of the former honour of Earl of Kinghorne.\n\n==Family==\nPatrick Lyon married Helen Middleton, daughter of [[John Middleton, 1st Earl of Middleton]], and his wife Grizel Durham, on 23 August 1662. They had issue:\n\n#[[John Lyon, 4th Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne]] (8 May 1663&ndash;10 May 1712).\n#Lady Grizel Lyon (1665&ndash;circa 1721)  married [[David Ogilvy, 3rd Earl of Airlie]], and had issue.\n#Lady Jean Lyon (1666&ndash;unknown), died young.\n#Lady Elizabeth Lyon (1666&ndash;before 1672), died young.\n#[[Patrick Lyon of Auchterhouse|Patrick Lyon]] (1669&ndash;1715).\n#Lady Elizabeth Lyon (1672&ndash;1739), married [[Charles Gordon, 1st Earl of Aboyne]], and had issue, married [[Patrick Kinnaird, 3rd Lord Kinnaird]], had issue, married Capt. Alexander Grant, no issue.\n#Lady Adelaide Lyon (1676\u20131698){{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}.\n#Charles Lyon (1679&ndash;1692), died young.\n\n==References==\n*{{cite DNB|wstitle=Lyon, Patrick (1642-1695)}}\n*{{cite book|last=Balfour Paul|first=Sir James|authorlink=James Balfour Paul|title=The Scots peerage|url=https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun08pauluoft|volume=XIII|year=1904 |publisher=D. Douglas |location=Edinburgh|pages=299\u2013303}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-reg|sct}}\n{{succession box |title=[[Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne]] | before=[[John Lyon, 2nd Earl of Kinghorne|John Lyon]]\n(as ''Earl of Kinghorne'')| after=[[John Lyon, 4th Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne|John Lyon]]|years=}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strathmore and Kinghorne, Patrick Lyon, 3rd Earl of}}\n[[Category:1643 births]]\n[[Category:1695 deaths]]\n[[Category:Earls of Strathmore and Kinghorne|3]]\n[[Category:Clan Lyon|Patrick]]\n[[Category:Extraordinary Lords of Session]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish peers]]\n\n{{Scotland-earl-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Lyon,_3rd_Earl_of_Strathmore_and_Kinghorne"}
